commit_message:
Cisco plugin should check for switch - vlan bindings

This commit fixes the issue where the Cisco plugin tries to create a
vlan twice on a switch if the first create is not bound to a port.
Also fixes an issue where the plugin tried to untrunk vlans from
a port for SVI interfaces.

Change-Id: Ifb13eb65d667367cffe120e1761d34f09b6d356d
Fixes: Bug #1233300

[{'created': '2013-09-06 11:08:52.000000000', 'message': 'Correct amount of samples in the chart

We need to always show some reasonable amount of samples in the chart.

It was hardcoded to 1000s time windows, when there will be a
several months of data, it will be a great amount of samples.

It needs to be changed to always show some reasonable amount of samples
(I would say 400)

Also exceptions added for unexpected states of dates.
Date_from has been changed to beginning of the day, and date_to to
the end of that day.

Fixes bug 1221566
Change-Id: I60cd0aa0882c5b8890d61b649c312d4f7e9ddf82
'}]
commit_message:
Correct amount of samples in the chart

We need to always show some reasonable amount of samples in the chart.

It was hardcoded to 1000s time windows, when there will be a
several months of data, it will be a great amount of samples.

It needs to be changed to always show some reasonable amount of samples
(I would say 400)

Also exceptions added for unexpected states of dates.
Date_from has been changed to beginning of the day, and date_to to
the end of that day.

Fixes bug 1221566
Change-Id: I60cd0aa0882c5b8890d61b649c312d4f7e9ddf82

'}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2013-09-20 11:45:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

When an alarm is created by an non-admin user, an implicit extra query field is added to ensure the alarm evaluation can't access statistics that the user couldn't ordinarily see:

  Query(field='project_id', op='eq', value=auth_project)

where auth_project would be the same as the alarm's project_id.

Wouldn't the same logic be also required now when the admin creates the alarm on behalf of another project?

Otherwise the admin would be delegating to the non-admin alarm owner her visibility onto all resources.

IIUC that extra implicitly-created additional query would 't be added by the current code in the case where the alarm creation request comes from an admin.

Cheers,
Eoghan"}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2013-09-20 14:48:24.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-20 15:17:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Works for me

'}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2013-09-23 14:50:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I might be missing something here, but seems to me that this leaks visibility onto statistics for resources that would not normally be visible to the non-admin user.

Say:

 1. ADMIN creates instance with INSTANCE_ID
 2. ADMIN creates alarm ALARM1 with --user DEMO --project DEMO --matching-metadata resource_id=$INSTANCE_ID
 3. DEMO creates alarm ALARM2 with --matching-metadata resource_id=$INSTANCE_ID
 4. ALARM1 ==> ok or alarm
 5. ALARM2 ==> insufficient_data

whereas I think we should have both alarms in insufficient_data, seeing as the instance stats should not be visible to the DEMO user.

The problem is that for user-created ALARM2, the api layer ensures that an extra implicit query is added to the threshold rule:

  {'field': 'project_id', 'value': $INSTANCE_ID, 'op': 'eq'}

whereas we don't get that for the admin-created ALARM1.

So would it be possible to change the semantics of sanitize_query so that the additional constraint on project_id is added even for an admin user, when that admin user is doing something on behalf of another user?

(This would restrict the visibility artificially when one admin user creates an alarm on behalf of another admin user, but that's a very edgy edge-case).

Cheers,
Eoghan"}, {'account_id': 7368, 'date': '2013-09-26 13:41:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: (1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2013-09-30 13:18:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

> So would it be possible to change the semantics of sanitize_query so that the additional constraint on project_id is added even for an admin user, when that admin user is doing something on behalf of another user?


I took a look a this, and it may be possible it is going to be ugly. AlarmThresholdRule builds the query with the project filter in validate() via sanitize_query. But at the point where the AlarmThresholdRule, there's no project context at all. The only project context we have is from the authentication headers set by the keystone middleware.

So at this point that requires to hack the AlarmThresholdRule to add a parameter that is not an attribute, but that would be the project the rule is created for.

Honestly, I think it would be a bad design. I think it's better to say that the admin can do whatever it wants, event shoot himself in the foot."}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2013-09-30 13:44:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Hi Julien,

I don't fully get the reasoning as to why it would be so ugly to add the implicit constraint on project_id when an admin creates an alarm on behalf of another user.

Is it because the way the code is currently structured, the call into the:

  _query_to_kwargs()->
    _sanitize_query()->
      acl.get_limited_to_project()

codepath now originates from AlarmThresholdRule.validate() and at that point in code we don't know the project_id of the intended owner of the alarm?

(whereas this alarm owner project_id would be required in order to check if it's not equal to the X-Project-Id header of the current request and hence conclude that the alarm is being created on behalf of another user)

Cheers,
Eoghan"}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2013-09-30 14:02:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Hi Eoghan,


> I don't fully get the reasoning as to why it would be so ugly to add the implicit constraint on project_id when an admin creates an alarm on behalf of another user.

Separation of concerns; a rule has no relation whatsoever with the alarm referencing it.

> Is it because the way the code is currently structured, the call into the:
> 
>   _query_to_kwargs()->
>     _sanitize_query()->
>       acl.get_limited_to_project()
> 
> codepath now originates from AlarmThresholdRule.validate() and at that point in code we don't know the project_id of the intended owner of the alarm?

Yes, that's what I tried to explain in my precedent comment. :)"}, {'account_id': 2813, 'date': '2013-09-30 14:32:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I prefer merged this as-is and rewrite the ACL part later because we can't fix just the AlarmThresholdRule use case, the AlarmCombinationRule have the same kind issue with alarm_ids (a admin can set a alarm_id that can be not visible by a normal user)."}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2013-09-30 15:00:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

> Separation of concerns; a rule has no relation whatsoever with the alarm referencing it.

True in theory, but the reality is that a detached threshold rule can't usefully exist outside the scope of an alarm, i.e. it has no purpose IIUC other than to encapsulate the condition of an associated alarm. Absent that alarm, the threshold rule is useless.

So IMHO, it would be pragmatic to do the ugly thing and close off the potential security hazard.

But I also take Mehdi's point that we need to consider combination alarms also in this context, so perhaps it would be wise to separate that whole issue off from this patch and consider it as a separate bug?

BTW this may be due to something local out-of-dateness in my devstack, but I just gave the patch a whirl and am seeing alarm creation fail with:

  http://paste.openstack.org/show/47701/

when an alarm is created by an admin, unless the project & user IDs are explicitly specified (due to data.project_id being equal to wsme.Unset in this case). Presumably you're seeing that succeed in your env?

Cheers,
Eoghan"}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2013-10-01 10:50:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Since this is the last patch waiting for RC1, I think it'd be better to try to find a solution in another patchset if that's ok for everyone.

As part the problem you see Eoghan, I've added a test case and a fix making user and project mandatory fields. It seems like the safest and more consistent way of doing this."}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2013-10-01 12:20:59.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-01 13:04:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Doesn't seem to work

commit_message:
Make Messages unicode before hitting logging

Some of the log handlers in the python standard library
are hitting issues with Messages since they check for
basestring types only, and attempt to coerce anything else
to string. This leads to Messages being coerced to bad encodings,
resulting in unhandled exceptions.

This change adds a check that looks for non-basestring
objects and coerces them to unicode before they hit the problematic
logging areas.

bug 1225099

Change-Id: I0bff6b52205e3c88db38876b8c6de1bd820f460a
Co-authored-by: Luis A. Garcia <luis@linux.vnet.ibm.com>

The commit message does not mention this at all.'}, {'account_id': 1926, 'date': '2013-10-01 19:04:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

Abandoning, thanks clint, I misunderstood the port number and though it did nothing for icmp.'}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-10-01 20:10:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'm not so sure that it has to be abandoned, just explained. There are useful things in ICMP that deserve to be allowed. In fact usually it is the other way, we want to block pings to avoid being an easy reflector, but allow good things through that aid our host in keeping connections healthy."}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-10-01 21:38:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

single host ping is fine, same bandwidth in as out; and yes we may want more icmp permitted. *stateful* logic such as PTMUd should Just Work, and if it doesn't thats a neutron bug:  we should only need to manually permit things that TCP doesn't itself need."}]

commit_message:
feat (proxy/admin): allow partition modifications

This patchset adds one new method to the partitions API
- PATCH /v1/partitions/{partition}

This patch implementation uses jsonschema to achieve self-documenting,
strict format validation of the incoming input.

The partition storage controllers are modified accordingly, as are the
tests.

Change-Id: If7da1cac3d8ad98c27dc45eb121bd351f1c7c102
Implements: blueprint placement-service
Closes-Bug: 1230841

'}, {'account_id': 6476, 'date': '2013-09-25 01:14:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Hi,
The *default* behavior should be to use a path that is writable. Horizon should not try to use a path next to the local_settings.py file, which by default in the (Debian) package is in /etc/openstack-dashboard (which is *not* a place where to have runtime writable files). The default behavior should to use something in /var. Please do that.

One way to do things would be to use the default home directory of horizon, which is /var/lib/horizon in the Debian package case. That would work. The folder currently doesn't exist, but I can change the packaging and make this happen."}, {'account_id': 6476, 'date': '2013-09-25 01:26:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

In fact, there is /var/lib/openstack-dashboard/ that can be used. It is currently owned by root / root, but we could change it so that it is owned by www-data / www-data.'}, {'account_id': 5280, 'date': '2013-09-25 15:22:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

That's out-of-scope for what I'm trying to achieve here.

The problem I'm trying to solve is that, when changing the behaviour from the default of scribbling files in silly places, the software still demands that it be able to scribble files in those silly places, or it refuses to start.

The default behaviour is fine for devstack, et. al, and production deployments should be providing a sensible local_settings.py anyhow, so I see little value in changing the default behaviour."}, {'account_id': 6476, 'date': '2013-09-25 16:59:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

According to Arno Toll, the maintainer of Apache in Debian, writing in /var/lock/apache2 is fine, as long as there's no clash with the files from Apache itself, and if Apache2 is started before doing anything in /var/lock/apache2.

Now, I read from you:

"The default behaviour is fine for devstack, et. al, and production deployments should be providing a sensible local_settings.py anyhow, so I see little value in changing the default behaviour."

I strongly oppose to this kind of view. What the developer should provide is a working default for production, not for devstack so that it can work for the development environment. I would say that it's the opposite way: fix devstack so that it can do what it needs, and don't pollute the production.'}, {'account_id': 5280, 'date': '2013-09-25 17:47:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

The error I see in that approach is that it shifts the conversation to "where should it try to write things by default?", which is a pointless argument.  I don't care.  I can't care.  Because no matter what I choose, somewhere, according to someone, my decision is wrong.

The only sensible approach to this problem (in my opinion) is to make it such that users/admins can override the default if it is not deemed suitable, and to make doing so as painless as possible.  The fact that admins need to account for the default behaviour, EVEN IF THEY ARE CHANGING IT, is the core of this bug, and what the patch fixes.  Scoping the fix any larger than that is to invite madness.'}, {'account_id': 4264, 'date': '2013-09-26 11:38:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

IMHO local_settings.py is something, distributions should set. 

Off-topic:
I could imagine to write to '/tmp', especially if your distro has such a feature like 'private temp', where each user has it's own /tmp."}, {'account_id': 6476, 'date': '2013-09-26 13:08:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Each time I raise the topic that the upstream default is not the best, I am being told that I should manually patch the file. Yes, it's possible to patch configuration files at the distribution level. I have done a lot of that in Neutron, which provides a not-useable-by-default configuration file (eg: it wouldn't work at all). Though this means that each distribution has to be aware of the needed change, and that work of patching the files will have to be duplicated among distributions (Debian, Ubuntu, RedHat, Gentoo, etc.). I believe OpenStack is the only project where upstream knowingly provides wrong configuration files, and believe it's normal, and that it's the role of downstream to fix it. This approach is IMHO error prone, and loss of time on both sides. This patch and launchpad bug is a proof of it. If you still believe that it is ok, then I am afraid that we will have more of this kind of issues, and I would like to avoid it.

I would suggest that at least, some comments written in big letters should be added by default in the configuration file, so that nobody misses it.

Best however, would be to detect if we are running under devstack, and use a different path in different environment, so that everyone is happy.

By the way, I'm afraid we cannot write in /tmp, because the .secret_key is a known filename, and in /tmp we cannot do that. The feature with the security against the symlink attacks in /tmp is only present in newer kernel, and neither Precise or Wheezy have a recent enough kernel to handle that."}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2013-09-28 01:03:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Thomas Goirand,

"Detecting" running under devstack is by far the wrong approach.  Devstack modifies configuration files all the time.  Correct approach would be to ensure Devstack used a sane location for it's runtime regardless of the default (requires a patchset for devstack).

I wont argue the other points, as I don't actually have a strong conviction about them except that regardless of where it gets set by default, someone will think that it is wrong.  Best solution is pick the least wrong location?'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2013-09-30 12:48:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I think more important point than the default path is that the patch of secret key is tightly coupled with dashboard settings and it is not configurable.
At now SECRET_KEY itself is a configuration parameter but the path of the secret key should be configurable. It allows distributors or operators to configure the path of secret key as they want.

The settings forces distributors or operators to configure the argument of generate_or_read_from_file (i.e., os.path.join(LOCAL_PATH, '.secret_key_store')) and it looks tricky.

I prefer to SECRET_KEY_PATH as a configuration parameter. It looks much easier to configure and it suffices Thomas' request too.
(I am not sure we also need to take care of SECRET_KEY for backward compatibility if we adopt SECRET_KEY_PATH, but it can be done easily.)

What do you think?

If you think it is not a scope of this patch, I can post a patch soon on top of it."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-30 18:54:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: No score

Starting gate jobs.
http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 1816, 'date': '2013-09-30 18:54:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Looks good to me (core reviewer); Approved

I am in complete agreement that the way OpenStack has chosen to do all this with the settings file(s) is not ideal by any means.

This patch is still valid despite those objections.

I don't see it as advisable to change a fundamental behavior the day before we cut the RC, though.

amotoki's suggestion seems sane, but I'd like to see that vetted on the mailing list prior to being the solution we run with. The more "django"-esque way to do this is to actually specify the configuration file itself on the command line, but we seem to have done a good enough job of providing the right settings in other areas that people *don't* want to write a full config file of their own but *do* want to tweak one or two values.

I would even be open to revisiting the idea of "local_settings.py" entirely in Icehouse. I could see a case being made that we ship several example configurations and inform people to either use one of those as-is or to write their own and not use ours at all.

A lot of the way Horizon is still a legacy from the earliest days of the project, and I think reviewing this as a whole makes sense for the future.

So, with that in mind I'm going to merge this patch as it solves a real bug without changig the existing behavior. If this patch were introducing the flawed behavior for distros the objection would be a blocker. As it is, it is not. Let's not lose track of this issue though.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-01 07:08:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Fails

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-09-24 18:31:11.000000000', 'message': "Don't attempt to generate the secret_key until after loading local settings

Currently the settings.py generates a secret_key, then loads user
ovverides.  The former step requires write access in a directory
that the webserver has no real business trying to write to, which
is a security risk, amongst other things.

As a simple mitigation step, defer loading the default until after
the local_settings.py has been loaded.  Then the admins can decide
if/how the secret_key is stored (or not stored, as the case may be)
and in absentia of that, it uses the current behaviour of scribbling
files in odd places.

Fixes Bug: 1220884

Change-Id: I158702f9500563a4d16f6aefc1a3afea766b1e92
"}, {'created': '2013-09-24 20:24:11.000000000', 'message': "Don't generate the secret_key until after loading local settings

Currently the settings.py generates a secret_key, then loads user
ovverides.  The former step requires write access in a directory
that the webserver has no real business trying to write to, which
is a security risk, amongst other things.

As a simple mitigation step, defer loading the default until after
the local_settings.py has been loaded.  Then the admins can decide
if/how the secret_key is stored (or not stored, as the case may be)
and in absentia of that, it uses the current behaviour of scribbling
files in odd places.

Fixes Bug: 1220884

Change-Id: I158702f9500563a4d16f6aefc1a3afea766b1e92
"}]
commit_message:
Don't generate the secret_key until after loading local settings

Currently the settings.py generates a secret_key, then loads user
ovverides.  The former step requires write access in a directory
that the webserver has no real business trying to write to, which
is a security risk, amongst other things.

As a simple mitigation step, defer loading the default until after
the local_settings.py has been loaded.  Then the admins can decide
if/how the secret_key is stored (or not stored, as the case may be)
and in absentia of that, it uses the current behaviour of scribbling
files in odd places.

Fixes Bug: 1220884

Change-Id: I158702f9500563a4d16f6aefc1a3afea766b1e92

This is almost certainly not the right fix for this. Before format message was introduced - we were calling unicode or str in the extensions directly on the exception instead. This results in unicode being called on all the args as per python docs - so this behavior didn't change with adding the format_message method.

Also looking at the code - args[0] is almost always an instance of Message (if it's not - we forgot to wrap it in _() and it's a bug) so leaving the else branch makes no sense."}, {'account_id': 5371, 'date': '2013-09-24 14:45:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Nikola Dipanov, I'm not sure what the problem is your trying to point out in the first paragraph. Isn't the issue that we are casting the exceptions to unicode and need to be returning the messages (which are always args[0], since NovaException instantiates them so in the __init__ above.) The Messages objects well be set on webob.exc.HTTPException as the explanation, which will then be wrapped by Fault objects and translated in nova/api/openstack/wsgi.py like the rest of the Messages from other APIs.

I can see how the else statement is probably not needed anymore."}, {'account_id': 5511, 'date': '2013-09-24 15:02:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Sorry if I was not clear! What I tried to point out is that calling unicode() on an exception itself instead of format_message() would still result in the translation being lost. This is not related to this patch - it's just me pointing out that this has been an issue with exceptions for some time (always??) if what you propose will fix it.

If we chose to fix this this way - then we should remove the check completely and just always give webob exceptions the args[0] (which we can leave wrapped inside a 'format_message' method for convenience)."}, {'account_id': 5371, 'date': '2013-09-24 18:04:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Ok I think I understand now. You are correct that the unicode() casting was there before (looked at the git blame) and that would have been an issue before format_message as well. I will clean up the commit message to indicate that better.

The Message objects should be resolved to unicode through the course of execution eventually, so there shouldn't be a big difference there. I'll clean up the check in format_message()

Thanks for the feedback!"}, {'account_id': 5371, 'date': '2013-09-24 22:41:17.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-24 23:14:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Doesn't seem to work

Well if there is a glanceclient exception being bubbled up to the api (file and line please) - they cannot be transformed with .format_message() anyway since they are not inheriting from NovaException. We need a separate except clasue for them with appropriate message setting. 

Everything inheriting from nova exception should be covered by this and if it's not - it's a bug with the particular exception."}, {'account_id': 5371, 'date': '2013-09-25 18:11:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

So here is what I think is happening (having a hard time recreating):

The ImagesOneServerTestJSON tempest test gives nova an invalid image name, which then gets passed to glanceclient which tries to make it in Glance and gets back an exception which gets turned into a glanceclient HTTPBadRequest(). 

The nova portion that talks to glanceclient then makes an Invalid NovaException and passes the glanceclient exception in as the arg[0] to Invalid (https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/image/glance.py#L536). This then gets handed off as the explanation parameter when ex.format_message() is called with the new 'return self.args[0]' here (https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/api/openstack/compute/servers.py#L1406). This can't be serialized by jsontutils, since its a glanceclient exception and then it results in the CircularReference issue."}, {'account_id': 5511, 'date': '2013-09-26 07:39:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Thanks for the detailed investigation. 

IMO handing over an exception to NovaException as the first param is a bug that we should fix. format_message usage is still fine.

So in this case we need to stringify exc_value in https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/image/glance.py#L547 or even better yet - pass a meaningful string to exception.Invalid constructor.'}, {'account_id': 5511, 'date': '2013-09-26 07:48:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

If we can fix that glanceclient exception case - I am +2 on this."}, {'account_id': 5371, 'date': '2013-09-26 16:39:39.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 5511, 'date': '2013-09-26 16:40:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

commit_message:
Make Exception.format_message aware of Messages

Many API extensions are casting NovaExceptions
directly to unicode with format_message(),
which results in a loss of localization information
from the possibly wrapped Message objects.

This change lets Messages be returned from
NovaException.format_message() if possible, which
will then be translated and resolved to unicode
later when needed.

fixes bug 1229410

Change-Id: I818a35b1d7d910c4f058d870e69c5ff73e45c6bb

commit_message:
Fixes backup with multiple volume backend

The backup service now keeps a dictionary of managers
for each type of volume backend. If multi backend is
not in use (and volume_type is None) the current
volume_driver is used.

Change-Id: I66e91f3ce2cffaf2e2d07edfddc08b1480e2a37c
Fixes: bug 1228223

[{'created': '2013-09-24 08:04:23.000000000', 'message': 'Fix finish_volume_migration() on SQLAlchemy 0.8.x

In SQAlchemy 0.8.x "Unconsumed column names" warning became
an exception, so refering to a non-existent column in insert()
or update() call raises an error.

finish_volume_migration() calls Session.update() method passing
values of two non-existent columns as arguments (volume_metadata,
volume_admin_metadata, volume_type). These two are not table columns
at all, but rather SQLAlchemy models relationships.

As SQLAlchemy ORM implements Unity of Work pattern, we should not
really track changes to a model instance manually at all, because
Session class already does it for us. finish_volume_migration()
is refactored to take benefit of this fact.

Fixes bug 1206561

Change-Id: I4513e3155a7dc6dcbd1c95aa9c14d1e1e5d02ab4

commit_message:
Fix finish_volume_migration() on SQLAlchemy 0.8.x

In SQAlchemy 0.8.x "Unconsumed column names" warning became
an exception, so refering to a non-existent column in insert()
or update() call raises an error.

finish_volume_migration() calls Session.update() method passing
values of two non-existent columns as arguments (volume_metadata,
volume_admin_metadata, volume_type). These two are not table columns
at all, but rather SQLAlchemy models relationships.

As SQLAlchemy ORM implements Unity of Work pattern, we should not
really track changes to a model instance manually at all, because
Session class already does it for us. finish_volume_migration()
is refactored to take benefit of this fact.

Fixes bug 1206561

Change-Id: I4513e3155a7dc6dcbd1c95aa9c14d1e1e5d02ab4

commit_message:
fix(proxy): forward marconi headers

Proxy uses the `requests` library to dispatch requests to
multiple marconi servers.  When the result comes back, update
the proxy response headers with the marconi responses.

Change-Id: I151580f174f1a0fc1edca23b43bb7256bcf568fe

commit_message:
feat(mongodb): Partition data across multiple databases

This patch causes data to be partitioned across multiple databases in
order to reduce writer lock contention. The "queues" collection is
isolated in its own database, while the messages collection is partitioned
across several other databases. The number of partitions is configurable.

For example, if the number of partitions is set to 4, these databases
will be created in MongoDB:

    marconi_queues
    marconi_messages_p0
    marconi_messages_p1
    marconi_messages_p2
    marconi_messages_p3

Implements: blueprint mongodb-multidb
Change-Id: I399f4a39e5377a381aef489b046bc14155ccb75b

commit_message:
Fixes errors logging in as a user with no password

A traceback in passlibe happened when trying to login as a user that
didn't have a password set.  This gave an unexpected status code. This
patch makes the server return a 401 instead.

Change-Id: I9cc64aeefb9e7488579482d4ee95df198af70801
Partial-Bug: #1226466

commit_message:
Build all Install Guides and HA Guide in gates

Build books the same way we build them for publishing:

Build all three variants of the Install Guides if we check building.
Since we introduce os specific sections, the guide might build for one
variant but not the others.

In case of failure, the variant is shown like:
Building all queued 1 books now...
>>> Build of book install-guide (for Ubuntu) failed (returncode = 1).

Also, generate the xml file for the HA guide and build it.

Add generated file bk-ha-guide.xml to .gitignore

Add parameter -B for building to mvn to silence download progress

Run test.py and validate.py through pep8 and fix any issues

Change-Id: Icfb4587e7c08050d1b65dddc5a3a810a8bf12f5a

'}, {'account_id': 2733, 'date': '2013-09-28 11:04:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

The note is helpful as it is not obvious how external access works and it seems natural to boot to the external network directly. I must look into why nova even allows you to do that - it would be better if it didn't.

But the note could be misleading as it suggests that floating IPs are required for external access. Actually, the instance will have external access even when it does not have a floating IP. This access is outbound only via the SNAT gateway in the uplinked neutron router. Floating IPs are only needed when you want external machines to be able to establish connections to the instances. This is a one-to-one DNAT mapping between the floating IP and the internal IP."}, {'account_id': 2448, 'date': '2013-09-28 15:13:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: (1 inline comment)

commit_message:
Add simple note about attaching neutron networks

I managed to follow the documentation properly for this example, however
something that was not clear to me was which networks attached inside
your VM.  So now, we display a little note hoping to help future users.

Also rename file from *pertenant* to *per-tenant*.

Change-Id: I0c4cbf9ae2ebb27037cbcc3b6cdf87069f69a16c
Signed-off-by: Paul Belanger <paul.belanger@polybeacon.com>

away from 'name' to 'flavorid'. However flavorid is also not unique.

commit_message:
get_all_flavors uses id as key to be unique

Change I1b0c93b3e12714a5c0798aa87c9e3fe9bc14519a fixed returning
deleted flavors by changing the get_all_flavors dictionary key
away from 'name' to 'flavorid'. However flavorid is also not unique.

This patch fixes get_all_flavors to work properly using the 'id' as
the dictionary key. This allows flavors to be created with flavorid's
that were previously deleted and then have them all returned when
get_all_flavor(inactive=True) is used.

Fixes bug 1215295 properly

Change-Id: I357a804fe9f012143c996d66b9719c4f46f60e86

Update attach interface api to use new network model

Remove legacy network, mapping network info usage, use new
network model, update related unit tests for this change.

Closes-Bug: 1229517

(10 inline comments)

If I understand the problem correctly, the problem is that in logging.LogRecord.getMessage the Message object is determined to be non-unicode (not even basestring), and its str()'d, then when it's tried to be promoted to unicode() that breaks. So, the problem we are fixing with this patch is the fact that Message needs to be considered a basestring, preferably unicode.

Now, the premise by which the Message was changed to immutable, I think is incorrect:

    "The implications of this change are that messages are no longer
    translated when they are rendered; they are translated when
    they are created and, from the user's perspective, they are
    immutable, *because the built-in text types are immutable.*"

You can certainly have class inherit from unicode (so that the main problem is solved) and yet have that class be mutable.
In this particular case, given the nature of what we are trying to do, i.e. delay translation, I think it makes sense for us to use the same object (that should be treated as a unicode hence should be one), and just translate its representation whenever we need. Like it is right now.

So, I am leaning towards not-changing to immutable, both because of the incorrect premise, but also, I think its risky we'd have to test a lot of stuff again.'}, {'account_id': 8001, 'date': '2013-09-25 23:11:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Luis, we must extend the built-in text type in order for the logic to work correctly. That text type is immutable, so there isn't any option to not be immutable.  It's really that simple.  You are wanting a built-in text type (unicode in py27) to be mutable, but it is not. Note that overriding the __unicode__ and __str__ methods is not a way of circumventing the fact that unicode is immutable, because not all operations involving strings will call those methods.  For instance, if I create a unicode object initialized to "string a", but have its overridden __unicode__ method return "string b", some logic will see that string as "string a" and other logic will see it as "string b", depending on how they access the string data.  That is not acceptable behavior. I'm not advocating this approach as a preferred design, I am advocating it as the only viable choice in terms of what we need these objects to do.  The design you are suggesting does not work.'}, {'account_id': 8001, 'date': '2013-09-25 23:25:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Below is an example script that shows how a class that extends unicode  with overridden __unicode__ and __str__ methods behaves:

http://pastebin.com/HwdE6di2'}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2013-09-25 23:30:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(3 inline comments)

I'm surprised it will even let you return different values from __str__ and __unicode__.  I looked into doing something similar to this a while back and my experience was that Python threw an error when I started messing with the value in those functions.  Of course, this example is simpler than what I was doing so there's probably some important difference I'm just not remembering.

I left a couple more comments inline.  I'm still trying to understand all of the implications of this change though.  Inheriting from immutable objects is tricky business. :-)"}, {'account_id': 8001, 'date': '2013-09-26 01:03:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

In response to comments along the lines of "this doesn't look immutable": the key phrase regarding immutability is "from the user's perspective, they are immutable", meaning someone who is using these objects as strings.  Message objects are still going to have attributes that can be changed, but changing those attributes will not change the string data, since that is immutable.  The attributes are kept so that all the information that was necessary to create the immutable string is kept intact so that it can be used to create the changed string that is used to initialize new Message objects as part of an operation such as being modded or being translated.  Also, changes to attributes happen internally and are not something that end users should need to worry about.'}, {'account_id': 8001, 'date': '2013-09-26 01:56:05.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 11.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-26 01:59:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Works for me

In response to the comment about it being bad if __unicode__ and __str__ were implemented differently...that was not the point I was trying to make.  When dealing with a unicode object or an instance of a child class of unicode, even if the __unicode__ and __str__ methods returned equivalent data, it is unacceptable if what they return does not correspond to the byte data that was used to initialize the unicode object.  If you look at the first example script I posted, you'll see that some operations access the data used to initialize the unicode object, while others call the __unicode__ or __str__ methods.  Put another way, it would be like having a String object in Java where string.equals(string.toString()) is false.  It would be very bad to have a String object that does not return itself when its toString() method is called, because people using such a string wouldn't know which one is the correct one to use--the String itself or what its toString method returned.  I can only hope that it is abundantly obvious that such ambiguity is bad.  In python 2.7 the standard way of identifying whether something is a string is to check to see if it is an instance of basestring. Because Message extends unicode which extends basestring, it would be reasonable for logic to treat Message objects like any other immutable string.  As the sample script demonstrates, you can print or otherwise render an instance of a class that extends unicode without ever calling its __unicode__ method. Programmers would reasonably expect there to be no difference between printing a unicode object or printing what its __unicode__ method returned, so we cannot assume that our Message objects' __unicode__ method would always be called, especially if they are passed into third-party modules."}, {'account_id': 8001, 'date': '2013-09-27 11:02:29.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 15.'}, {'account_id': 8001, 'date': '2013-09-27 11:04:28.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 16.'}, {'account_id': 8001, 'date': '2013-09-27 11:09:14.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 17.'}, {'account_id': 8001, 'date': '2013-09-27 11:26:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13: (1 inline comment)

But please consider the previous comment. Thank you,'}, {'account_id': 8001, 'date': '2013-09-30 20:00:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 18:

I guess it's just a difference of opinion. At a high level, to me the original design was flawed in that a string class was enhanced and the one enhancement that was made did not fit in with the rest of the class's behavior: every operation except translation operated as if on an immutable object and returned a new object, whereas translation involved setting an attribute value. I think a consistent design, like the one being reviewed, is better.

In any case, arguably the least invasive change isn't always the best one. Over and over again, I have seen implementations with "hack" feels to them remain in code for years, because the problem happened to be identified at a sensitive time and a minimal fix was implemented, and no one ever went back to do the job properly. I can see that the code in the proposed alternative works in terms of the test cases, but frankly I'm surprised that it does work, and to me that's a bad sign--it feels like a hack. I also think classes should be extended because their functionality is being enhanced--you needed to override practically every method of unicode to get things to work, while the proposed change overrides far fewer.

Finally, I think doing something like redefining how a well-know built-in function like "_" works should be done with utmost care, worrying not only about all the ways the objects it produces are currently being used, but also worrying about the unanticipated ways they might be used in the future.  I believe that programmers who are unaware of the alternative implementation of this method being used in OpenStack should not be surprised by the objects it produces behaving in an unexpected manner--debugging is difficult enough when well-known Python functionality works as expected.  For instance, while I was working on an approach similar to the alternative that is being proposed (unicode object initialized with one string, __unicode__ returning something else), test cases were failing with error messages stating that two strings were not equal, even though the strings that were printed to the log were identical. I would not be surprised if it's quite common for people to use the "print" statement when looking at values of variables in pdb--they are going to be awfully confused when what is printed is different than what other logic is saying the object is.  I don't think it is practical to put a comment next to every use of the "_" method indicating to the developer that the objects returned by it will reflect one value when printed via the "print" statement and another value if rendered in some other way, for instance via a logger.

In the end, we're talking being cautious about two different aspects: how invasive the change is vs. the soundness of the design.  I understand that reasonable people can disagree about which is more important and even whether one design is better than the other.'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2013-10-01 16:36:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 18: Do not merge

[{'created': '2013-09-13 18:15:58.000000000', 'message': 'Change fixed Message encoding to dynamic

openstack.common.gettextutils.Message.__str__ had utf-8 as the hard-
coded encoding which can create problems when dealing with messages
with translations containing double-byte characters, because
operations such as logging will attempt to decode the str objects
using the default encoding and fail if it is not utf-8.

fixes bug 1225099

Change-Id: I9b67e57f4f9bea2883e76c7b20651879770d47bd
'}, {'created': '2013-09-13 18:57:48.000000000', 'message': 'Change fixed Message encoding to dynamic

coded encoding which can create problems when dealing with messages
with translations containing double-byte characters, because

fixes bug 1225099

Change-Id: I9b67e57f4f9bea2883e76c7b20651879770d47bd
'}, {'created': '2013-09-25 01:22:52.000000000', 'message': 'Change Message to extend built-in text type

The original fix had misdiagnosed the underlying problem. For
background, this is how strings are processed by logging in py27:

1. The message object to be logged is added to the log record via
the "msg" attribute.

2. logging.LogRecord.getMessage does an isinstance(msg, basestring)
check.  If negative, the value of the "msg" attribute is replaced
by str(msg).  This was happening with openstack.common.gettexutils.
Message objects, since they did not extend either unicode or str
(py27).

3. The logging formatter combines metadata and the message to be
logged with the formatting string via a mod operation. If any of
the mod parameters are unicode objects, all of the other parameters
are promoted to unicode objects as part of the mod operation. If
the Message object in step 2 contains double-byte characters and
the default encoding is 'ascii' (which it usually is), the
promotion of the str object that was derived from the Message
object fails because it cannot process any non-ascii bytes.

Because the logging module and other string-processing modules
cannot be changed to accommodate Message objects, the only
alternative was to alter the Message class so that it extends
the built-in text type (unicode in py27) for double-byte
characters. This change entails some complications...

These built-in text types are immutable, while the Message
objects were coded to be mutable in terms of the locale. The
relevant methods and test cases had to be altered to accommodate
the new, partially immutable objects.  This was necessary,
because some operations will obtain the string data from the
immutable unicode data, while other operations call the
__unicode__ method instead.  Every change to a Message object
that alters the value returned by __unicode__ method therefore
requires that a new Message instance, one with updated
unicode data, be created.  From a consumer's perspective, the
only affected functionality is translating the string into
a different locale.  This is now done via the Message.translate_into
method, which will return a new Message object with the correspoding
updates to the immutable unicode data. (Consumers should no longer
alter the locale property directly.) Note, however, that the
underlying message key and other instance data remains unchanged,
so that a message that has been translated into a different locale
can be translated again--no information that is necessary to
render a new translation is lost.

closes bug 1225099
fixes bug 1229800

Change-Id: I9b67e57f4f9bea2883e76c7b20651879770d47bd

'}, {'created': '2013-09-25 19:00:24.000000000', 'message': 'Change Message to extend built-in text type

The original fix had misdiagnosed the underlying problem. For
background, this is how strings are processed by logging in py27:

1. The message object to be logged is added to the log record via
the "msg" attribute.

2. logging.LogRecord.getMessage does an isinstance(msg, basestring)
check.  If negative, the value of the "msg" attribute is replaced
by str(msg).  This was happening with openstack.common.gettexutils.
Message objects, since they did not extend either unicode or str
(py27).

3. The logging formatter combines metadata and the message to be
logged with the formatting string via a mod operation. If any of
the mod parameters are unicode objects, all of the other parameters
are promoted to unicode objects as part of the mod operation. If
the Message object in step 2 contains double-byte characters and
the default encoding is 'ascii' (which it usually is), the
promotion of the str object that was derived from the Message
object fails because it cannot process any non-ascii bytes.

Because the logging module and other string-processing modules
cannot be changed to accommodate Message objects, the only
alternative was to alter the Message class so that it extends
the built-in text type (unicode in py27) for double-byte
characters.

The implications of this change are that messages are no longer
translated when they are rendered; they are translated when
they are created and, from the user's perspective, they are
immutable. The way to translate a Message instance is to call
its translate_into method; the Message instance that is returned
is the translated message, which itself can be translated.
In other words, translating a Message object does not alter
the underyling message ID.

closes bug 1225099
fixes bug 1229800

Change-Id: I9b67e57f4f9bea2883e76c7b20651879770d47bd

logged with the formatting string via a mod operation. If any of
the mod parameters are unicode objects, all of the other parameters
are promoted to unicode objects as part of the mod operation. If
the Message object in step 2 contains double-byte characters and
the default encoding is 'ascii' (which it usually is), the
promotion of the str object that was derived from the Message
object fails because it cannot process any non-ascii bytes.

Because the logging module and other string-processing modules
cannot be changed to accommodate Message objects, the only
alternative was to alter the Message class so that it extends
the built-in text type (unicode in py27) for double-byte
characters.

The implications of this change are that messages are no longer
translated when they are rendered; they are translated when
they are created and, from the user's perspective, they are
immutable, because the built-in text types are immutable.
The way to translate a Message instance is to call
its translate_into method; the Message instance that is returned
is the translated message, which itself can be translated.
In other words, translating a Message object does not alter
the underlying message ID.

closes bug 1225099
fixes bug 1229800

Change-Id: I9b67e57f4f9bea2883e76c7b20651879770d47bd

commit_message:
Change Message to extend built-in text type

The original fix had misdiagnosed the underlying problem. For
background, this is how strings are processed by logging in py27:

1. The message object to be logged is added to the log record via
the "msg" attribute.

2. logging.LogRecord.getMessage does an isinstance(msg, basestring)
check.  If negative, the value of the "msg" attribute is replaced
by str(msg).  This was happening with openstack.common.gettexutils.
Message objects, since they did not extend either unicode or str
(py27).

3. The logging formatter combines metadata and the message to be
logged with the formatting string via a mod operation. If any of
the mod parameters are unicode objects, all of the other parameters
are promoted to unicode objects as part of the mod operation. If
the Message object in step 2 contains double-byte characters and
the default encoding is 'ascii' (which it usually is), the
promotion of the str object that was derived from the Message
object fails because it cannot process any non-ascii bytes.

Because the logging module and other string-processing modules
cannot be changed to accommodate Message objects, the only
alternative was to alter the Message class so that it extends
the built-in text type (unicode in py27) for double-byte
characters.

The implications of this change are that messages are no longer
translated when they are rendered; they are translated when
they are created and, from the user's perspective, they are
immutable, because the built-in text types are immutable.
The way to translate a Message instance is to call
its translate_into method; the Message instance that is returned
is the translated message, which itself can be translated.
In other words, translating a Message object does not alter
the underlying message ID.

closes bug 1225099
fixes bug 1229800

Change-Id: I9b67e57f4f9bea2883e76c7b20651879770d47bd

commit_message:
Redirect output of pool create call

When I ran create-nodes as instructed in devtest.md, I got back
a bogus MAC such that "SEED_MACS=Pool default defined".  It looks
like there was some output from the pool create call to virsh, so
redirect that command's output to /dev/stderr as is done for the
configure-vm call.

Change-Id: Ic3163178765a418b8c91a59ebbb04e18d236bcb7

[{'created': '2013-09-20 14:42:36.000000000', 'message': "Add mmh3 and pylru

MurmurHash3 is a fast and well tested non-crypto hash function.
We can not use python's built-in __hash__() because it gives different
results for same input in different execution (to against pre-
calculated collision attack).  While your our is just to distribute
data onto multiple databases.

Python3 has LRU decorator in functools, but Python 2 does not.
pylru offers an LRU decorator in Python 2, and shows noticeable
performance improvement.

The requirements above are needed by the openstack-marconi project.

Change-Id: I3b9b771142fdf9eb5813715132befd7324ee1362

commit_message:
Add mmh3 hashing package

MurmurHash3 is a fast and well tested non-crypto hash function.
We can not use python's built-in __hash__() because it gives different
results for same input in different execution in Python 3 (to against
pre- calculated collision attack).  While your our is just to distribute
data onto multiple databases.

** Needed by the openstack-marconi project.

Change-Id: I3b9b771142fdf9eb5813715132befd7324ee1362

[{'account_id': 7368, 'date': '2013-09-26 14:51:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

'}, {'account_id': 7368, 'date': '2013-09-26 15:06:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Change in keystone that broke these:

https://github.com/openstack/python-keystoneclient/commit/20e166fd8a943ee3f91ba362a47e9c14c7cc5f4c#diff-bd6505432da8629a1e85b25349a8d5d0'}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2013-09-26 15:06:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'm confused about this one, I don't see a python-keystoneclient release on pypi that's newer than:

  https://pypi.python.org/pypi/python-keystoneclient/0.3.2

That 0.3.2 release was cut on 2013-08-22, and launchpad suggests 0.3.3 isn't due til 2013-10-01 .

So I'm wondering how a commit to python-keystoneclient that only went in on Sep 12th could be breaking our build?

Cheers,
Eoghan"}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2013-09-26 15:19:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

litong's right actually, the commit date is anterior to the 0.3.2 release date BUT it got merge AFTER 0.3.2; so the next version of python-keystoneclient will break Ceilometer."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-26 15:19:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Doesn't seem to work

commit_message:
keystone client changes in AuthProtocol made our test cases failing

class AuthProtocol from python-keystoneclient project has been
changed. It no longer has the member auth_protocol, auth_port and
auth_host, our test cases need to be changed to test against other
members like auth_uri.

Change-Id: I3af86bb773fef80054bb0ad3820e1b8510bf67cb
fixes: bug #1231491

commit_message:
issue an error log when cannot import libvirt

the ceilometer-compute-agent doesn't issue an error log even if libvirt
couldn't be imported.

This patch fixes this problem.

Change-Id: I91bd80a694983da3eab93866a649a61b09d133c7
Closes-Bug: #1232961

commit_message:
Add support for openSUSE 12.3

devstack has been tested on and is regularly used on openSUSE 12.3.
Support is available via the opensuse-cloud mailing list:

  http://lists.opensuse.org/opensuse-cloud/

(This should also be added to the website in a separate review request.)

Change-Id: I74049984806c592c60a926999ac5484139bd9dd0

commit_message:
Remove tools/openstack*

Remove the tools/openstack* scripts - they're no longer maintained,
and there are several alternative documented ways to install openstack
with Heat now, so we should direct people to those instead.

Change-Id: I649f384f6acc3d7edab25f104f8e9d7e0050f2c1
Partial-Bug: #1182428

commit_message:
Raise/Relax WebTest requirement to match Keystone

All OpenStack modules I can find are using an unbounded
WebTest test-requirement, and at least Keystone fails gating
with 1.3.3. Raise requirement to 2.0, which seems to match reality.

Change-Id: I7ffef924f93256b9d8d6191b5f79de937b05e2b0

Um, let's not add that header support. There is no reason for it when you can just use content-length (and since we don't pass metadata in headers in v2.)"}, {'account_id': 6737, 'date': '2013-09-06 08:13:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Hey Mark,

We still need a means for the client to provide the image size if chunked transfer is being used i.e. if content-length is not/cannot be set. In this case, as implemented in 1220197, the glanceclient allows for the caller to pass in a value for x-meta-image-size. If there is another/better way to do it please let me know but i do think we should include this somehow since have to revert to the slower resize-befoe-write is really non-optimal.'}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2013-09-06 12:35:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Hi Ed,

After reading Mark's comment very quickly (and perhaps not following all the subtleties) I think what he's is saying is:

1) if you know the size in advance use Content-Length and do not use transfer encoding.

This will require a change in common/http.py to detect the presence of the content length header and if present switch to not use chunked transfer encoding

2) if you don't know the size in advance then don't supply a content-length header, and use chunked transfer encoding

'x-image-meta-size' is a v1 concept and is unlikely to get approved in v2."}, {'account_id': 6737, 'date': '2013-09-06 13:10:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

ok I will remove the x-image-meta from here and the corresponding glanceclient fix.'}, {'account_id': 6737, 'date': '2013-09-06 13:18:09.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-06 13:46:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Works for me

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-08-19 13:25:08.000000000', 'message': 'RBD store support when image_size set to zero

Currently glanceclient upload() with v2 API does not provide
image size to RBD store add(). We now work out the image size
and resize the image we are writing to accordingly.

Change-Id: I014c4b71c77c92b9876786d1ba438cdb90f83233
Fixes: bug #1213880
'}, {'created': '2013-09-04 12:54:52.000000000', 'message': 'Allow v2 api upload support x-image-meta-size and rbd store support zero size image

Currently, the glanceclient upload() with v2 API does not provide
image size to RBD store add(). We now work out the image size
and resize the image we are writing to accordingly.

We also allow v2 API upload to accept x-image-meta-size.

Glanceclient support for this will added as part of bug 1220197

Change-Id: I014c4b71c77c92b9876786d1ba438cdb90f83233
Fixes: bug #1213880

commit_message:
Add rbd store support for zero size image

If glanceclient does not provide image size to RBD store add() it
will create a zero-size image and fail when writing to it. If
provided with zero size we now work out the size of each chunk
being written and resize the rbd image prior to each write. This
will be much slower than if new the image size on create but it
will at least work.

There is a corresponding glanceclient fix to ensure content-length
is set if known by the glanceclient, see bug 1220197

Change-Id: I014c4b71c77c92b9876786d1ba438cdb90f83233
Fixes: bug #1213880

commit_message:
Fix cloudprompt

cloudprompt wasn't updating when OS_CLOUDNAME changed.  This adds
the necessary backslash to prevent it from being evaluated only
once.

Change-Id: I077e8f33e8f8a686e36a7d4b3ef6fc0d1fd33506

(5 inline comments)

Two main things here:

1. The changes in the test_servers modules (both v3 and non-v3) need the same fixes that I pointed out, i.e.

a) make the instance object version a static helper method in the fakes module you're already importing
b) create the instance object in the setUp method of the test class right away rather than convert self.instance to an object in each individual test case

Those changes should reduce the LOC here by quite a bit and clean it up.

2. I really dislike the copying of the fields list just to make the tests work, that's not maintainable. Move the copy of the expected_attrs into the _make_instance_list method and then remove the INSTANCE_DEFAULT_FIELDS[:] from the test cases. That will make the tests cleaner and make the _make_instance_list method more robust."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2013-08-28 16:34:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 16:

Jay, I spoke with Chris Behrens (comstud) in IRC today and he said that compute.api.get should definitely not load 'fault' by default as it will impact performance.  The fault field is loaded only as needed via the API for nova show and nova list.

So that should address your question in IRC this morning."}, {'account_id': 1030, 'date': '2013-08-28 16:40:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 16: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Yes.  We should not load 'fault' by default.  It's silly to join things by default that are only used in certain circumstances.

2) Why are you copying INSTANCE_DEFAULT_FIELDS everywhere?  There's no need to copy this.  Yes, it is a global, but it's never modified or never meant to be modified.  If something is modifying this somewhere, we should fix that.

3) A review of mine just merged that fixes a few issues with the Instance object that might address some of your stubbing issues.  As an example, 'fault' should not really be in INSTANCE_DEFAULT_FIELDS so it has been removed.  Maybe this solves some of the problems you were having.  Try rebasing on master.

4) Everyone else's comments."}, {'account_id': 7494, 'date': '2013-08-29 03:25:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 16: (4 inline comments)

For what it's worth, I think I originally said to put the helper method in fakes because the tests were already using fakes, but I'm OK with moving it to fake_instance.py also since that is more specific to stubbing out instances.

And yes, there is a lot of duplicated code in nova unit tests for stubbing instances (test_compute is another example that has it's own helper method for stubbing a fake instance dict and converting to an instance object).  In the nova meeting a couple of weeks ago John Garbutt was talking about looking at all of the duplication and trying to figure out a good way to consolidate it across the project.  I don't know where that is right now though, he mentioned something about bringing this up at the Icehouse design summit.

I don't like the idea of doing the instance dict->object conversion inline all over the tests, I think it should be consolidated into a helper method and used globally; again, see test_compute:

https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/tests/compute/test_compute.py#L296

Note that even in test_compute where it has it's own helper method to do the conversion, there are individual test cases that are using fake_instance to create the stub and then converting it to an object inline rather than using it's own helper methods.  So yeah, it's a mess, but we should consolidate and user helper methods wherever possible for new code - which this is - and if Dan wants it in fake_instance I think we should just have it there.  I don't see how having it in fake_instance instead of fakes makes any difference to the number of impacted test cases - you just need to import another module in the test cases already in this patch."}, {'account_id': 7664, 'date': '2013-09-11 18:23:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 27: No score

commit_message:
Fix loading instance fault in servers view

If VM schedule failed, then VM will be set to ERROR state,
but "nova show" does not show the fault of the VM.

The fix use lazy load to get instance fault if the instance
went to ERROR state.

Closes-Bug: #1212915

Change-Id: If286fd0176be8307c50b2a7c3534fff33fa5c10f

commit_message:
Refactor test cases related to instance object

After the blueprint unified-object-model, all of the instances
should be represented by an instance object but not a db
instance dict.

In some test cases, they are still using db instance dict,
we should change those test cases to use instance object.

The fix include three parts:
1) Add a new stub method fake_fault_obj in
nova/tests/fake_instance.py to help convert a dict fault to an
object fault.
2) Add a new stub method fake_instance_obj in
nova/tests/fake_instance.py to help convert a dict instance to
an object instance.
3) Make sure all test cases related to "fault" and "instance" passed.

Closes-Bug 1230125
Partial-Bug 1212915

Change-Id: Ie54fface139e4ad042b9a748c7409c3698875413

commit_message:
Code quality improvements in heat topology

Ensure that functions are not declared conditionally and
that they are declared before being assigned as callbacks.

This commit contains no code changes, only rearrangement
plus whitespace and semicolon fixes.

Fixes Bug #1226945

Change-Id: Ie549d48d0ea47d00d904b36555bd68c95ad12f49

commit_message:
Fixed xml response for share snapshot.

For now xml response for snapshots show/list isn't
full. Snapshot xml template was updated to make
response full.

[{'account_id': 7395, 'date': '2013-08-26 23:08:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: (1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 7395, 'date': '2013-08-26 23:18:04.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 7395, 'date': '2013-08-26 23:21:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I would appreciate any input on this patch. I am struggling with passing context information to engine/api.py. The alternative is to pass in a stack_identifier to format_stack in engine/api.py and handle the description/outputs in engine/service.py. The problem with this is that it changes the functionality of format_stack in the api.'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2013-08-27 12:56:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

In https://review.openstack.org/#/c/39760/6/heat/engine/service.py we discussed lazy-loading of Resources to speed up Stack.load(), rather than (further) de-encapsulating the database format. TBH I would prefer to see something like that happen.

BTW there's a good case for having a separate format_stack_minimal(), just to save bytes on the wire more than performance reasons per se. It's only out of laziness that we're still sending everything to the API for stack-list as well as stack-show ;)"}, {'account_id': 7256, 'date': '2013-08-27 16:11:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

While I don't think this is bad, per se, I do agree that lazy loading of stack resources is a Good Thing(TM). Also agree that perhaps a dedicated set of methods for getting just a minimal set of data for these sorts of calls makes sense."}, {'account_id': 7395, 'date': '2013-08-27 17:44:42.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 7395, 'date': '2013-08-27 17:49:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Thanks for your input Zane. Posted is an alternative implementation suggested by Randall Burt that would not break encapsulation, however still gives us the benefit of lazily loading the resource and dependency data. This is going to require several test changes, which I am going to hold off on until receiving more input.'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2013-08-28 10:13:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Yep, I would support something like this (commit msg needs an update btw).

A couple of suggestions:
* A quick grep shows that almost nothing external is using Stack.resources any more (and the few cases that are, probably shouldn't). Almost everything is accessed through __getitem__. Let's get rid of those few remaining cases. Then maybe it will be possible to just rename resources to _resources and put the lazy loading in __getitem__.
* Likewise, the only place setting dependencies is a filthy hack in update.py (I can say this because I wrote it ;). It's probably better to add a reset_dependencies() method that resets _dependencies to None instead of adding a setter method to the property."}, {'account_id': 7256, 'date': '2013-08-28 18:22:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: (2 inline comments)

Looking good. A few comments in-line but I think this is headed in the right direction. Regarding the __getitem__ vs the property (you know how I love my properties), is it sufficient to do the clean-up later or is it important enough to tackle in this change. I only ask so as to reduce the amount of code to review.'}, {'account_id': 7395, 'date': '2013-08-28 18:44:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: (1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2013-08-29 14:07:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I think it's preferable to do the cleanup first. In separate patches, naturally ;)

BTW I'm not at all against using @property here - "I screwed up my API and now I need to fix it without breaking backward compatibility" is a *completely* legitimate use case. It's just that we are so close to not needing backwards compatibility that I think it's probably simpler to just switch over.

It was always my goal after adding __getitem__ to Stack to eventually get rid of direct access to the resources dict, so this seems to be a good opportunity to finalise that long migration :)'}, {'account_id': 7395, 'date': '2013-09-11 15:23:45.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 7395, 'date': '2013-09-11 15:32:47.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 5494, 'date': '2013-09-11 15:32:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
Lazily load resources when loading a Stack

Stack-list is one of heat's slowest operations.
It uses the orm to fetch resources for every stack
in the database, then spends a lot of time deserializing
resource data. This patch forces resources and dependencies
do be lazily loaded.

bug 1214602
Change-Id: Ieec481cb8ab211054f8956090ad97a687c9a616b

(1 inline comment)

I don't think this works.  The translation system will only see "%s: %s" and therefore can't generate a translation for this message, since all of the contents are dynamically generated.

From cinder.pot:
#: cinder/api/middleware/fault.py:69
#, python-format
msgid "%s: %s"
msgstr ""'}, {'account_id': 7996, 'date': '2013-09-25 17:56:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Hi Eric, 

Thank you for the review. Let me try to clarify the approach. 
By wrapping the explanation message in _() we are actually creating a Message template, which can be translated by the Fault class. 

For example, before if a VolumeNotFound was raised we ended up with a string comprised of two strings:

    explanation = "%s: %s" -> "VolumeNotFound":  "Volume 99 could not be found."

Regular strings can't be translated.

After the fix, we end up with a Message comprised of a string and another Message:

explanation = Message("%s: %s") -> "VolumeNotFound":  Message("Volume 99 could not be found.")

When the Message gets to Fault.call() it can be translated and translation works recursively, so all messages in the "%s: %s" Message (which includes the CinderException explanation) will be translated.

In other words we are not trying to grab the string "%s: %s" from the .mo files, but we are creating a Message template, that can hold further Messages, which are actually loaded from the .mo files. Similar to the existing template in cinder.pot:

#: cinder/exception.py:182 cinder/brick/exception.py:88
#, python-format
msgid "%(err)s"
msgstr ""

Thank you,'}, {'account_id': 7996, 'date': '2013-09-25 17:57:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: (1 inline comment)

commit_message:
Fix translation of CinderExceptions in REST API

When creating a Fault from a CinderException wrapped in an
HTTPException, we were converting the inner explanation to unicode
before it was able to reach the Fault's call() method which is where
translation occurs, and unicode objects can't be translated.

This patch preserves the CinderException's Message object and puts it in
another Message object as the explanation to the HTTPException so it can
be translated.

Fixes bug: #1229967

Change-Id: Ida71908b639da32b4b85846a117ef21da2fe685b

    def create(self, name, data):
        resp = self.api.client.put('/job-binary-internals/%s' % name, data)
        if resp.status_code != 202:

commit_message:
Fix mandatory and optional args for create_volume

Calls to create_volume (both volume_rpcapi and scheduler_rpcapi) pass
mandatory args as optional and reverse. This patch fixes the calls to be
according to the function definition.

Also, fix the call to create_volume in the migration code where
allow_reschedule defaults to True, but we don't pass request_spec so it
prints a warning and disables it.

Change-Id: I9509f88866e0ae182f90ebdfca1fcf415ca60d19
Closes-Bug: #1230069

commit_message:
Fix Huawei HVS driver attaching volume error

If iSCSI initiator is not added to host, we will get https errors
for we find the initiator info by sending url with this initiator name.

This patch fixes the way of getting the initiator info.
First, get the all initiator info.
Then, find the one we need by name.

Closes-bug: #1230296
Change-Id: I92620374923fa136ee71fe6eb3af6e4c78a3d66b

commit_message:
Revert "Enable tenant isolation to tempest for neutron"

This reverts commit 3d84cf2d7c323750971cf2d27f3a4eaa26cb7a9f.

This is believed to be the cause for the massive increase in
neutron failures in the gate reseting other projects. Realize
this is just a work around.

Change-Id: Id3c59f3fe9ccbb869eb3200ef7ff2659409e2253
Partial-Bug: 1224001

commit_message:
python3: Fix traceback while running tests

Python3 changed the behavior of dict.keys such that it is now
returns a dict_keys object, which is iterable but not indeable.
You can get the python2 result back with an explicit call to list.

Change-Id: Ib104fe8ee3d37d833019b1a53557c27346d0fdc1
Signed-off-by: Chuck Short <chuck.short@canonical.com>

As for the Jenkins failures, I think your patch set 1 looks like the right fix given the discussion in the bug reports and the other stable/grizzly failure logs attached to the bug reports, but now it looks like devstack is failing with python-quantumclient in devstack which would be another aspect of the bug?

install: cannot stat `/opt/stack/new/python-neutronclient/tools/neutron.bash_completion': No such file or directory"}, {'account_id': 7368, 'date': '2013-09-27 12:37:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

That's a fair point, I didn't catch the d2to1 issue - sorry. =[

There are a few concerns I see here:

1. Why are global (upstream) requirements influencing grizzly backports for any OpenStack component?

2. If we are going to continue with #1, then we need to remove the redundant requirements here, since it creates confusion and potential issues down the road as we improve upstream's requirements. Like now, with upstream configured according to cliff handling its own dependencies.

3. The gate failing here appears to be devstack master branch being used to test quantumclient rather than devstack's stable/grizzly branch, meaning two different install client functions. The master one is trying to access a file that doesn't exist in quantumclient branch:

(master): https://github.com/openstack-dev/devstack/blob/master/lib/neutron#L393-L397

(stable/grizzly): https://github.com/openstack-dev/devstack/blob/stable/grizzly/lib/quantum#L351-L355"}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2013-09-27 13:38:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Yeah, I saw the same on the devstack issue, I don't know why stable/grizzly checks are running against master devstack, that seems like a bug in infra but I don't know where to resolve that.

I added Sean to see if he knows, but I know he's also investigating some other gate issues today."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2013-09-30 16:40:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

The backing bug is invalid now since it's been fixed here:

https://github.com/openstack/python-neutronclient/commit/cbb83121c09f95b00720f494ab5f424612ac207d

There is a new issue for stable/grizzly patches though and that's reported in bug 1233264."}, {'account_id': 7368, 'date': '2013-10-01 12:42:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Abandoned

Already fixed in another change.'}]

devstack gates because it clashes with other requirements.

commit_message:
Convert generator to list in Heat list API call

The generator being returned by heatclient didn't like
being iterated multiple times (as when doing a multiple
delete through the stacks table).

Fixes bug #1224393

Change-Id: I01482c0fadcf145fe99806983d9a1dc6f50ac56a

And more importantly, get rid of d2to1 references.

Skipped test-requirements because of webtest and I need the d2to1 change
in.

Fix sphinx build

We're using oslo.sphinx now, we don't want to reference non-existing
local themes.

commit_message:
Fix DB API issue when searching for specific event

Due to review #45207 last patchset, climate.db.sqlalchemy.api
event_get_all_sorted_by_filters had been rewritten to add an extra param
, which was not exposed to climate.db.api

Change-Id: I1955435d861569770f195be46cb51da799cde247

commit_message:
VMware: Fix volume detach failure

The VMwareVCDriver method "detach_volume" is missing the "encryption"
argument and thus does not conform to the driver API. Adding the missing
argument solves TypeError being thrown when detaching a volume.

Change-Id: Ib785c2b2cf4c25deed272f8e3f0f47abe6139d1c
Closes-Bug: #1226826

[{'created': '2013-09-20 15:06:04.000000000', 'message': 'enabling trove to work in multi-region deployment

In a multi-region environment with trove in both, troveclient
currently throws an error regarding ambiguous endpoints if a
region_name kwarg is not passed in. Now passing in the
services_region.

Change-Id: I0a2cea3d532680549a594e8bf0e9df1d15f37cde
Closes-bug: #1227888
'}]
commit_message:
enabling trove to work in multi-region deployment

In a multi-region environment with trove in both, troveclient
currently throws an error regarding ambiguous endpoints if a
region_name kwarg is not passed in. Now passing in the
services_region.

Change-Id: I0a2cea3d532680549a594e8bf0e9df1d15f37cde
Closes-bug: #1227888

@afazekas, can you share the reproduced steps? I'm interested in that. Thanks for working on this."}, {'account_id': 6549, 'date': '2013-09-23 14:12:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

TBH I have little concern for the performance, under current implementation all notification message be sent by one qpid connection and I agree this could cause some race issue under heavy concurrent situation without necessary lock protection. But after your change, glance-api need connect to qpid every time when upper layer code emit each message, generally the connection establishment is an expensive operation for whole stack (Operation System+Lib+PID), it involved a lot of resource allocation and process handling, so I consider it will be better if we just use OS's lock mechanism to prevent this dead lock issue.

I agree you using select and thread module of eventlet to make improvement on low level of cause, it make sense to me."}, {'account_id': 6549, 'date': '2013-09-23 14:21:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Fixing glance-api hangs in the qpid notifier

Glance-api was able to hang in qpid notifier under heavy image creation load.

The ``thread`` and ``select`` modules used by the python-qpid for managing
the AMQP connection. When the eventlet was not able to switch between threads
because leaded to hang and/or pipe(2) leaking issues.

* Monkey patching the ``select`` and ``thread`` modules to be  eventlet friendly
  in order to avoid hanging issues.

* The reference to the connection object in the QpidStrategy
  was replaceable by a concurrent thread, which could cause various issues.
  Using just local variables for storing connection object in order to avoid
  concurrent unsafe manipulation.

Fixing bug 1229042

Change-Id: I8fa8c4f36892b96d406216cb3c64854a94ca9df7

commit_message:
Add notification for pause/unpause instance

When pause/unpause instance, there are no notifications, this
will cause someone cannot know when pause/unpause operation
would be finished.

All other instance operations do have notifications. We should
also add notification support for those two operations.

Change-Id: I5b8cc33a5992f5f028a3220217dcf7a0288d150d
Closes-Bug: #1043861
