"}]
commit_message:
Change per-tenant router use-case so tenant uplinks router

The per-tenant router use-case example implies that only the admin user is
is able to set the external gateway on the tenant's router. This is wrong
and this patch changes the example so the tenant does it instead.

Fixes bug: 1233167

Change-Id: Iec82581d3dad145be9d2327b9cf48b290a864f7a

commit_message:
Create links between FWaaS resources

Part of blueprint fwaas-horizon

This commit creates cross links between FWaaS resources
and resolves FWaaS resource UUID in tables to its name.
This helps users to track FWaaS resources.

This commit also improves an error handling when an error occurs
during retrieving a resource detail via API call.
While previously a detail page without item values is displayed,
now the index page is displayed for such case.

Closes-Bug: #1229433

Change-Id: I4357b5c275ab75163f0afc7158b4c1edb8cecd6c

commit_message:
Set vol driver initialized before deleting volumes

Move the call to set_initialized before calling delete_volume in
init_host.  The delete_volume method has a precondition that the
driver be initialized.

Closes-Bug: #1232177

Change-Id: Ie73bd30e0ab80d489ab61ba8a60fac51ccb505b5

Move the policy enforcment for force_host and force_node into the
_handle_az() method so that any violation of policy is detected before
the DB entry for the instance is created.

Fixes bug: 1220220

Change-Id: Iaf6df4f8df6cca71fcb860244ccf758d7908b8f1

commit_message:
Policy check for forced_host should be before the instance is created

Move the policy enforcment for force_host and force_node into the
_handle_az() method so that any violation of policy is detected before
the DB entry for the instance is created.

Fixes bug: 1220220

Change-Id: Iaf6df4f8df6cca71fcb860244ccf758d7908b8f1

commit_message:
Configurable cell_class in DataTable

There are two changes in this proposal. One is to move the logic
for extracting cell data from the row datum (and handling auto columns)
to the Cell class, into a separate method for easy extending. The
second is to make that extending possible by making the cell class
configurable in the DataTable's meta.

Those changes are supposed to make it easier to extend the DataTable
with new kinds of cells -- for example, cells that contain an editable
widget, a progress bar, an icon, etc. as well as make it easier to
modify the behavior of the auto columns -- for example, by making it
possible to have some of the multi_select checkboxes preselected. Those
changes would also make it easier to integrate DataTable with a Django
FormSet.

Right now, in order to modify any of the proposed Cell.get_data
behavior, one has to make their own Row class and practically copy-paste
the whole Row.load_cells method, as there is no easy way to extend it.

Change-Id: Ida1df646e330cc0db65cf8649d6d3ea4731ee527
Closes-Bug: #1229677

[{'created': '2013-09-24 20:15:08.000000000', 'message': 'Move location of HTTPException in swift_testing

While doing some work around swiftclient Python 3 support, httplib
imports were changed to use six.moves in order to access httplib in Py2
and http.client in Py3. Tests related to those changes are failing
because these functional tests are depending on HTTPException being
a name in swiftclient.client. These tests should acces that name from
its canonical location in httplib (or, eventually, a Py3 friendly
location like six.moves).

Change-Id: I6335d465574045daedab47e5fe23c415d171a83a
'}]
commit_message:
Move location of HTTPException in swift_testing

While doing some work around swiftclient Python 3 support, httplib
imports were changed to use six.moves in order to access httplib in Py2
and http.client in Py3. Tests related to those changes are failing
because these functional tests are depending on HTTPException being
a name in swiftclient.client. These tests should acces that name from
its canonical location in httplib (or, eventually, a Py3 friendly
location like six.moves).

Change-Id: I6335d465574045daedab47e5fe23c415d171a83a

usages are incremented/decremented on a per user basis, but there are
quotas stored for a NULL user on each project.  These quotas are never
decremented leading to invalid quota limits being enforced.

This migration performs a full sync of quotas, and removes the NULL user
rows for each project.

commit_message:
Full sync of quota_usages

Migration 203 added a user_id column to the quota_usages table.  Now
some usages are incremented/decremented on a per user basis but there
are preexisting usages stored with a NULL user, and some usages are
tracked per project but there are usages stored with a user_id.  These
quotas are never decremented leading to invalid quota limits being
enforced.

This migration performs a full sync of quotas, and removes the incorrect
rows for each resource type.

Change-Id: Iff96f81e36b135df94a6f25c9443d0e9333bd18f
Closes-Bug: #1212798

commit_message:
Import translations from Transifex for Havana RC1

* Import ~100% completed translations
* Update language list in openstack_dashboard settings.py
* Remove all old translations in the previous release
* Remove English compiled PO (MO) files

commit_message:
Memory persistence backend improvements

* got rid of globals -- all data now belongs to backend instance;
* be more accurate and consistent with copying saved data.

Change-Id: I3e54415e23b7df03e48de3d6c0800f0149051560

commit_message:
Update to latest tox configs

Overriding the install_command is important to ensure that unexpected
pre-release software does not get installed. use_develop skips the
tarball steps in virtualenv creation.

Change-Id: I001b903f6ca4ef13e3e137f4144f8d7e989bb0f0

commit_message:
File header changes and rules

On this week I saw several negative responses related to the
LICENSE application. So this change makes it more consistent and
adding a File rules entry to the HACKING.rst.

The tempest/api/identity/__init__.py change also contains a dead code removal.

Change-Id: I9c81b0b6fb19cee14a5ec2a3da98dc271e648e15

commit_message:
Server+User leak detector

Adding a small extensible tool for detecting and reporting
strange/unwanted
situations which can happen during the test runs.

This part is contains a small server+user leak detector
on the API level.

This tool will be extended with many API based check, and
not API based checks like:
* sql db entries
* volumes
* running hypervisor processes
* volume disk files
* ...

The basic concept is recording the situation before the test suit run,
and comparing situation after the test suite run.

Implements: blueprint stop-leaking

Change-Id: I3390761665dd78d082220b6e30a2384b25b8a26c

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-09-13 22:39:30.000000000', 'message': "Add root CONF_DIR variable.

Add a root CONF_DIR variable so that config files for the various
OpenStack services can be grouped together under one dir that isn't
shared with the rest of the system like /etc. This is useful for
capturing the config files in devstack-gate after testing.

Note that horizon, apache, and tempest are not changed as their config
file dirs are not generic like the others.

Change-Id: I3462e3089eb121cd8590fca50f9d1f5cacc8d2a1
"}]
commit_message:
Add root CONF_DIR variable.

Add a root CONF_DIR variable so that config files for the various
OpenStack services can be grouped together under one dir that isn't
shared with the rest of the system like /etc. This is useful for
capturing the config files in devstack-gate after testing.

Note that horizon, apache, and tempest are not changed as their config
file dirs are not generic like the others.

Change-Id: I3462e3089eb121cd8590fca50f9d1f5cacc8d2a1

[{'created': '2013-07-11 10:21:43.000000000', 'message': 'Increasing the default floating range

The 11 effectively usable floating IP limit can cause issues,
with the parallel test runs.

Increasing the fixed IP range to /24 from /28.

Change-Id: I090f64289caa5dc8c136649c42bcf1809cec80fe
'}]
commit_message:
Increasing the default floating range

The 11 effectively usable floating IP limit can cause issues,
with the parallel test runs.

Increasing the fixed IP range to /24 from /28.

Change-Id: I090f64289caa5dc8c136649c42bcf1809cec80fe

commit_message:
Allow setting necessary config options for MidoNet

Closes-Bug: 1224869

If the MidoNet API server, username, password, or
project ID differed from the default, the VM was
failing to launch.

This patch makes the above config options settable
via the neutron_plugins script to resolve this problem.

Change-Id: I9604d9a2e73f1a5b2c88ae4e6b83fa7f2dda18c0

[{'created': '2013-09-23 10:18:44.000000000', 'message': "Fix rare problem where external daemon is not started

Before daemon.py and external_process.py start a new process in an IP
namespace, they first check if the corresponding pid file exists. If it does,
they check if a process with that pid is running, and if so, and it's a Python
process with the uuid of the router or network in its command line, then they
consider the process to be already running and do not start it.

However they get this wrong if the pid file is stale, and if a rootwrap
process is running a command in the same IP namespace and it just happens to
have the same pid as in the stale file. This is very unlikely, but possible, and
results in the metadata namespace proxy not being started.

This patch prevents that by changing these modules so they do not mistake
commands with 'ip netns exec' as the process they are trying to start.

Fixes bug: 1223369
Change-Id: Id7c6eb5019ef61f87fd6edfa65ba2cb95fcd45dd
"}]
commit_message:
Fix rare problem where external daemon is not started

Before daemon.py and external_process.py start a new process in an IP
namespace, they first check if the corresponding pid file exists. If it does,
they check if a process with that pid is running, and if so, and it's a Python
process with the uuid of the router or network in its command line, then they
consider the process to be already running and do not start it.

However they get this wrong if the pid file is stale, and if a rootwrap
process is running a command in the same IP namespace and it just happens to
have the same pid as in the stale file. This is very unlikely, but possible, and
results in the metadata namespace proxy not being started.

This patch prevents that by changing these modules so they do not mistake
commands with 'ip netns exec' as the process they are trying to start.

Fixes bug: 1223369
Change-Id: Id7c6eb5019ef61f87fd6edfa65ba2cb95fcd45dd

commit_message:
Adds ability to configure various clients used by the Heat

This commit adds config sections [clients_nova], [clients_swift],
[clients_neutron], [clients_cinder], [clients_keystone] and
[clients_ceilometer].  These sections contain additional
configuration options for corresponding OpenStack clients.
Currently those are only SSL-related setting ca_file, cert_file,
key_file and insecure. Note, than not every client library is
currently capable of utilizing all of the SSL settings.

There is also a plain [clients] section that holds shared client
options. Each option searched first at specific group (clients_xxx)
and if it not found there then the value from [clients] group
are taken (or default values if there is no such setting in this
group). This allows defining shared configuration that would be
used by most (or all) clients without repeating the same settings
for each and every client separately

Closes-Bug: #1213122
Change-Id: Id7747f47d9006ff0b11b9e67b6e18cad78c2c026

commit_message:
Fix SQLAlchemy constraints.

The SQLAlchemy < 0.7.9 constraint is meant to prevent accidental
upgrades to 0.8, but 0.7.10 has been released : installing keystone
will fail on a mirror that only has the most recent release of 0.7,
which a fresh openstack pypi mirror will have, as the global
requirements only constraint to < 0.7.99, not < 0.7.9.

Change-Id: Ia43ba377884c77f0c349dff50c060eebcd3ac0d0

commit_message:
Refactor code to use execute_as_root()

execute_as_root is a small wrapper that passes down
the correct root_helper and run_as_root flags. This
simplifies the code and avoids missing root_wrapper
args.

Change-Id: I6b5ceec8b142420165a30ca5b6df17c5b177349a

commit_message:
Provide support for glance arbitrary url

The fact that nova.conf's glance_api_servers list requires those
endpoints to be using the standard URI format is lacking. Nova
should provide a method to support glance arbitrary url.

Fixes bug #1220131
Implement blueprint nova-enable-glance-arbitrary-url
DocImpact

Change-Id: I9a35b910e07f175b930d4a51598faccb20698bc3

[{'created': '2013-09-30 14:49:01.000000000', 'message': 'Dont retry if target creation succeeds

The target creation retry loop was not breaking when
the target was succesfully created.  This is "sometimes" ok,
however in other cases this will actually cause a failure in
the second create and the backing Lun will be deleted and not
created again succesfully due most likely to a busy status on the

Closes-Bug: #1226337
'}]
commit_message:
Dont retry if target creation succeeds

The target creation retry loop was not breaking when
the target was succesfully created.  This is "sometimes" ok,
however in other cases this will actually cause a failure in
the second create and the backing Lun will be deleted and not
created again succesfully due most likely to a busy status on the
target.

Add a break in the try block.

Closes-Bug: #1226337

commit_message:
Shellify all of devtest.sh.

It is possible now to run a full devtest setup from the script.
We have also now inverted the greed in the image name globbing when
loading images into glance. This is necessary to support building in a
directory with a period in the name (i.e. ~/.cache/).

Change-Id: I75acd6cbc583b7c18a615ad72ee595977441df59

api: return 404 if a alarm is not found

The patch return 404 instead of 400 if a alarm is not found

Fixes bug #1232041

commit_message:
Default to the ML2 plugin in Neutron instead of OVS

In Icehouse, the OVS and LinuxBridge plugins are being deprecated in
favor of the Modular Layer 2 (ML2) plugin. This change modifies
devstack to default to ML2 when Neutron is used for networking.

Fixes bug 1220745

Change-Id: I9a4c84b04727a710219fc11f862a655309ffb99b

commit_message:
Fix logging of failed baremetal commands

Subprocess output is bytestrings, not unicode, so %r is the right
format to use.

NOTE: Also make sure message internationalized.

Change-Id: Ifa57ca594f17b95e5d0c428fbeb48c8b02ff885a
Fixes-Bug: #1223253

commit_message:
Volume timeout is set too low

* The default for volume timeout is not sane.
  This, if not set, produces a non functioning
  installation. Resetting to 60s instead of 2s.

fixes bug 1226496

Change-Id: I71cf7c138a30c30cfbc3e3fd1d3385bad5fd1cc4

commit_message:
Warn if multiple providers found

If many providers produce a given name as an output
it is nice to be able to warn the user when this is
happening as early as possible.

Change-Id: Ia5f963120827c0228d318a799c8bc3c21b9687ac

commit_message:
chore: Expose commit hash in version module

This patch adds a marconi.version.verify_sha() convenience function,
so that continuous integration scripts can use it to verify marconi has
been installed correctly and/or to detect when the installed version is
out of date (i.e., that "import marconi" pulls in the latest version of
the library.)

Change-Id: I645c3a55a837d588fec55fa9b5c1ec579026b8f5

commit_message:
Fix logging

self.task['uuid'] is wrong because task is instance of rally.task:Task
not dict. So it should be self.task.task['uuid'] or to simplify we should
just override Task.__getitem__()

Change-Id: I7f58639a33943aba682904a5792f141aaf2e2f64
Closes-bug: #1233409

commit_message:
Run seedrc before cloudprompt

Running cloudprompt before seedrc doesn't do anything because
OS_CLOUDNAME isn't set yet.

Change-Id: I6c0190ccaa1a762b24a89c7fc4b45875d321d4ec

commit_message:
Don't allow mutating operations on the underlying graph

Instead of allowing a direct graph return of the underlying
graph_flow graph we should return a frozen version instead so that
users of the returned value can not mutate the graph without going
through the graph_flow pattern (which could have undesired and
harmful side-effects if this occurs).

Change-Id: I38b35119d6e7bd7387b8ab467eba53aee5500629

commit_message:
Add milestone option to reviews_for_bugs

This script is extremely slow for larger projects.  A common use case
for the script is to find the reviews for an upcoming milestone.  Add an
option to limit the results to a milestone, which vastly reduces the
launchpad API traffic from this script.

Change-Id: I7326a68264b6b84765b92abb6efc8e3ff60e399e

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}, {'account_id': 7393, 'date': '2013-09-30 21:33:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Hi GuoHui,

The scenario we are trying to fix is when an instance errors out during resize and the task state remains in either 'resize_migrated' or 'resize_finish'.  Resource tracker when updating resources would ignore the instance while calculating the resource because the instance host and node are set to destination and the migrations are not considered because the instance is in 'error' state.

Meanwhile if the source host is filled up, we will not be able to do a revert resize. 

Ideally we would want to retain resources both on the source and destination until the resize is complete."}]

commit_message:
Resource tracker considers instance in error during resize

This fix would retain resource for an instance on the source
node which errored during resize. This would fix scenarios
where the instance could not be reverted because the node
 filled up before the revert.

Fixes bug 1228374

Change-Id: Iba657d149eceb6987bae3db64607ea4c679410c2

commit_message:

The two integrated projects that use WebTest, neutron and keystone,
both have it listed with no pin. This was a carry-over entry from
the initial merge, so I do not believe it was an intentional choice.

commit_message:
Adapt WordPress_NoKey to changes in str_replace

Adapt naming of parameters to the str_replace function to implementation
changes in that function so the replacement works correctly. The following
change introduces exact string matching, so we have to change from the
previous python string template based notation:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/47772

Note: the change to the HOT template depends on the change above being
merged (or gets necessary as soon as this change is merged).

Change-Id: I229bee76771b0b0f691943f9fa8ceaa8393de781
Closes-Bug: #1229741

commit_message:
api: return 404 if a resource is not found

This also checks for the error message that is returned, and fixes a
problem with the error encoding middleware that was doing double JSON
encoding.

Change-Id: Ieb39a991ddc9ecba0a7e71450a1e57ede18ccbe6
Fixes-Bug: #1218760
Fixes-Bug: #1208552

commit_message:
Set sane defaults for required conf params in trove/common/cfg.py

The following conf options are required and should have their defaults
set to sane values which make sense for the reference implementation:
ignore_dbs, ignore_users, admin_roles, and api_extensions_path

Change-Id: I2d78e9a06cb56832297d38a8fc4608964bca6976
Fixes: bug 1226496

tox 1.6 was released, which means that we can now take advantage of the
feature we added to it - which is using setup.py develop to install the
code into the virtualenv. The logic was taken from run_tests.sh - so the
performance issues around using tox vs. using install_venv should now be

Fixes-Bug: #1233213
'}]
commit_message:
Upgrade tox to 1.6

tox 1.6 was released, which means that we can now take advantage of the
feature we added to it - which is using setup.py develop to install the
code into the virtualenv. The logic was taken from run_tests.sh - so the
performance issues around using tox vs. using install_venv should now be
gone.

Change-Id: Ib011a9add595696f5db5fe596db9d3d60f46d038
Fixes-Bug: #1233213

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-09-27 21:40:28.000000000', 'message': "Increase the default for num_iscsi_retries

It appears that the issue in the repeated boot
from volume tempest test may just be an issue of not
giving the iscsi sub-system enough time for everyting
to propogate.

The test does a sequence like:
  Create bootable volume
  Boot from vol
  Create snap of that volume
  Create volum from that snap
  Boot from that new volume

Everything seems ok up until the last boot from volume.
In the case of the last BFV, we create the target succesfully
and nova actually finds the target when issuing the sendtargets command,
and it succesfully logs in to the target.  This seems to indicate that the
target was in fact created correctly, however when we try and actuall
perform the connect/attach to /dev/disk-by-path we exceed the retries
before the iscsi mount is actually available.

This change will bump the retry count from 3 to 5, this seems a bit
excessive but it may help with debugging.  We're also adding a few
more log statements that might aid in debugging as well.

This likely will NOT close the bug, but only aid in gathering more info
so I'm not adding the closes xxx info here.

Change-Id: I701cef1fadf81218ca8a189f0c22b6337f3c8713

commit_message:
Increase the default for num_iscsi_retries

*******************

DO NOT MERGE
Running this through rechecks to collect data on the
bootvolume test failures

******************

It appears that the issue in the repeated boot
from volume tempest test may just be an issue of not
giving the iscsi sub-system enough time for everyting
to propogate.

The test does a sequence like:
  Create bootable volume
  Boot from vol
  Create snap of that volume
  Create volum from that snap
  Boot from that new volume

Everything seems ok up until the last boot from volume.
In the case of the last BFV, we create the target succesfully
and nova actually finds the target when issuing the sendtargets command,
and it succesfully logs in to the target.  This seems to indicate that the
target was in fact created correctly, however when we try and actuall
perform the connect/attach to /dev/disk-by-path we exceed the retries
before the iscsi mount is actually available.

This change will bump the retry count from 3 to 5, this seems a bit
excessive but it may help with debugging.  We're also adding a few
more log statements that might aid in debugging as well.

This likely will NOT close the bug, but only aid in gathering more info
so I'm not adding the closes xxx info here.

Change-Id: I701cef1fadf81218ca8a189f0c22b6337f3c8713

commit_message:
Add API uuid <-> id mapping

On the API side, when creating a new node or port, translate 'chassis_id'
and 'node_id' from uuid to id, internally id will be always used to do
database operations. The opposite will happen when returning data back
to the user the internal id will be translated to an uuid.

Change-Id: I84782268c4317b4eec53fdcdfc6cb2b901b22780

[{'created': '2013-09-26 16:39:38.000000000', 'message': "Don't wrap Glance exceptions in NovaExceptions

Exception objects from glanceclient are not serializable
in Nova and shouldn't be directly wrapped inside NovaExceptions.
The glanceclient portions of Nova that translate from Glance
to Nova should be creating new corresponding exceptions
independent of the Glance counterparts.

Change-Id: Ifbe992796f8c5738ae350617d41a9c312fa8ab94
"}]
commit_message:
Don't wrap Glance exceptions in NovaExceptions

Exception objects from glanceclient are not serializable
in Nova and shouldn't be directly wrapped inside NovaExceptions.
The glanceclient portions of Nova that translate from Glance
to Nova should be creating new corresponding exceptions
independent of the Glance counterparts.

commit_message:
VMware: Fix bug for root disk size

The code would not configure the root disk size to that specified
in the flavor. This was always the size of the glance image.

Fixes bug: 1226052

Change-Id: I75ea766e3c96a2e0ad8a8d7cf7d24d80e1f94050

commit_message:
Clean CONF out of brick initiator

This is part 1 of the work needed to
remove CONF from the brick subproject.
This patch removes the CONF usage
completely from the initiator portion of brick.

Partial-Bug: #1230066

Change-Id: I5ea5f60e3559bd5abd97b3d86a78b2501106057d

commit_message:
Pass through args and kwargs in brick connectors

This is a change needed to help remove CONF usage
in the brick/remotefs/RemoteFsClient.
RemoteFsClient can then pull the values from the caller.

Change-Id: I591ecb5df95a797249cff75a9887a7c89dff405e
Partial-Bug: #1230066

commit_message:
Script to save devtest environment

Add a write-tripleorc script that writes out the enviornment variables
that are set from the devtest instructions to a tripleorc file.  The
tripleorc file can then be sourced from a new shell if you happen to
have lost the shell you were running the instructions from.  Very
handy if say your suspended laptop eventually runs out of battery on a
long flight home :-).

Change-Id: I28aae9a1fae62019b8b7f8074586adc5f48ef366

commit_message:
xenapi: set vcpu cap to ensure weight is applied

There is a bug in XenServer 6.1 and 6.2 that means the vcpu weight
we set is ignored if the cap is not also set.

Setting the cap to its default of 0, meaning no cap, to ensure the
weight value is applied.

Fixes bug 1213960
Change-Id: I367a9afe188734cf5e95c01fc014b9044003d6e3

commit_message:
add an explanation to the sqla requirement

people keep trying to "fix" this to a broken statement, and I now
realize the reasons for this being added are basically lore lost
in the mists of time. So document it.

The wrong fix is no longer blocked in our gate because we force
install newer pip on our devstack nodes (otherwise lots of other
things break).

Change-Id: I048e33d101a0c09adabac6d17cbc0ff23fba19e7

Using required=True is a good idea, because in some places, it will produce a more meaningful error message when the option is not provided, thanks!

Still, I think the help messages must be fixed: there is no way for people to know what options __must__ be passed simply by reading the output of 'ceilometer help <subcommand>'. Maybe this could be done by editing the 'arg' decorator, so that it automatically adds 'Required' to the 'help' message when 'required' is 'True'. WDYT ?"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-10 13:35:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Works for me

commit_message:
Add user-data and config-drive information to End User Guide

These three files have not been included in any of the current guides
and we have broken references to them:
common/section_user-data.xml
common/section_nova_cli_userdata.xml
user-guide/section_nova_cli_config-drive.xml

This patch adds them to the End User Guide and fixes references to
them.

Note: I'm not 100 per cent sure that the End User Guide is the right
place to add these. Please double check and advise.

Partial-Bug: #1225093

Change-Id: I12538a6c8f8f84e5a469a8b63b1dd1b71f44d21a

filename of an include directive that was not detected by our
validation scripts since we did only check whether a file
included a modified file but omit checking pom.xml for
modification of included files. So, if bk-* gets modified,
we do not notice it and therefore won't build the book.

a couple of comments.

"}]
commit_message:
Improve checking for modified files

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/48726/ introduced a typo in the
filename of an include directive that was not detected by our
validation scripts since we did only check whether a file
included a modified file but omit checking pom.xml for
modification of included files. So, if bk-* gets modified,
we do not notice it and therefore won't build the book.

With this change, the books will be build. I also added
a couple of comments.

Change-Id: Idba71ac4f9f1e4de2c414bcc0110351966df3248

commit_message:
add: enum34

Rationale: enum34 is the official backport of Python 3.4 enums to
Python 2.4+ and 3.1+. Bringing this package in would allow for designs
involving constants to be developed in a more robust fashion that
relying on strings and/or ints.

Change-Id: I8ddf6bd16f5968535e142cc547ccffe0ae0f14db

Maybe the original flag 'recreate' is confusing, but as Jay Lau mentioned, the "rebuild" flow is not going to be affected by this bug fix. 
The 'recreate' flag will be true only in cases when rebuild called from evacuate api. 
By design evacuate starts instance rebuild on a host different from instance original host and that's why the check for instance nonexistence must occur (similar to create instance scenario).'}, {'account_id': 4601, 'date': '2013-09-09 18:46:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Maybe a new flag can be introduced to differentiate the rebuild flow from the evacuate flow? Something like 'evacuate=None'?"}, {'account_id': 7494, 'date': '2013-09-09 23:27:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Check instance exists or not when evacuate

When evacuate instance to another host, similar to instance create,
nova compute must make sure the instance not yet exist on the host.

Currently there is no check for this, the fix was add the checking
of instance exist or not when evacuate.

Fix bug 1216501

Change-Id: I3ccbd5db5174904e17ffa8f9236ca4e1a09f4dbe

commit_message:
Fix stopping instance in sync_power_states

When an instance is marked as stopped in the DB but is actually running,
the sync_power_states periodic task will try to stop it.  It does this
using the compute API.  The compute API checks the vm state before
proceeding.  The STOPPED state is treated as invalid.  This patch allows
the caller to bypass the state check and makes use of that in this
periodic task.

Change-Id: I447b6dbd1da72ed33067659708e1755bf8c933d0
Closes-bug: #1226965

commit_message:
Fix chown fail for nfs file without necessary permission

chown failed in case of volumes on nfs export when the
permission is not granted on the storage system. Upload
volume only requires read access on the nfs file and hence
chown is not neccessary when current user has read permission.
Chown only executed when read is not granted to the user.

Change-Id: Ifa8eff7e79c6e4f15a1feb7cabec8cae8a0b0a83
Closes-Bug:#1221205

commit_message:
Should not add metadata filter rules if disable metadata proxy

The metadata filter rules should not be added into iptables if Neutron
metadata proxy is disabled.
This patchset fixes this issue by adding a condition when adding metadata
filter rules to iptables.

fixes bug #1224290

Change-Id: Ie686c71027093f17f0a280777f31a11c7d055e7e

commit_message:
Fix typo in mkoderer username

This commit just fixes the entry for mkoderer on the list of tempest
core team members. It was previously misspelled which meant it wasn't
showing up properly on the list as a Tempest core team member.

Change-Id: Ifb054a283f5354c9b67dc48a22e6c384cbd88e13

unit tests with coverage option, the overall test code coverage
percentage is low due to the enclosure of the common libraries.
Adding the coverage config file will exclude these modules in
the code coverage report so that developers can easily see if
new test cases has increased or decreased the code test coverage.

to see the code coverage report, following the following steps:

   file in your browser and scroll down to the bottom to see the
   total number. (this patch makes that number to be 90%)
   <ceilometer_root_dir>/cover/index.html

To keep up with this effort, whenever you add new code, please
run the test code with coverage option and make sure your new
code and test won't decrease the total percentage. If it did,
that means you may have new code un-tested :-)

commit_message:
add coverage config file to control module coverage report

Ceilometer copies oslo common code into its code stream. When run
unit tests with coverage option, the overall test code coverage
percentage is low due to the enclosure of the common libraries.
Adding the coverage config file will exclude these modules in
the code coverage report so that developers can easily see if
new test cases has increased or decreased the code test coverage.

to see the code coverage report, following the following steps:

1. In ceilometer root directory, execute the following command
   ./run-tests --coverage
2. Once the test run completed successfully, open up the follwoing
   file in your browser and scroll down to the bottom to see the
   total number. (this patch makes that number to be 90%)
   <ceilometer_root_dir>/cover/index.html

To keep up with this effort, whenever you add new code, please
run the test code with coverage option and make sure your new
code and test won't decrease the total percentage. If it did,
that means you may have new code un-tested :-)

Change-Id: I277c243b6aadb0e8524915452326ed875e14ce9c

`printf` will fail.

Change-Id: Ie6c4d075928f47b17cc413d537fc31c9d0734bdb
Signed-off-by: Tomas Sedovic <tsedovic@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Set locale for the profiling printf command

When LC_NUMERIC is set to a format that doesn't use a decimal point,
`printf` will fail.

Change-Id: Ie6c4d075928f47b17cc413d537fc31c9d0734bdb
Signed-off-by: Tomas Sedovic <tsedovic@redhat.com>

Currently if the disk bus is not specified in LibvirtConfigGuestDisk, it
will fail to render XML. According to libvirt documentation - this is an
optional attribute of the target element.

"}]
commit_message:
Libvirt: allow empty disk_bus in guest disk config

Currently if the disk bus is not specified in LibvirtConfigGuestDisk, it
will fail to render XML. According to libvirt documentation - this is an
optional attribute of the target element.

This patch allows for a None disk bus, since libvirt driver's block
device data defaulting logic considers this a valid case.

Closes-bug: #1229273

Change-Id: Idd0a5043e03f2c3580b388f97a542ffe916179a8

operator can configure.

commit_message:
Add check for the external interface

Because ovs-vsctl add-port simply updates the OVS db, it will
dutifully add it to the configuation even if the external
interface doesn't exist on the system.

The end result of this is that traffic will silently die as it
attempts to go to the wire.

This check verifies the external interface is present on the system
and doesn't attempt to add it to the external bridge unless it exists.

Change-Id: Ic93e21e34bc14fac06e764e06f335630c3c6eac4

[{'created': '2013-09-27 17:41:51.000000000', 'message': 'Updates to work with latest setup-baremetal cmds.

TOCI updates to work with the latest triple-incubator
scripts.

Recenly we changed setup-baremetal and register-nodes in
the incubator so that the way it handles MACS works differently.
Specifically we now only pass the MAC addresses we want
register-nodes to actually use (previously that script contained
some rather janky logic to decide which MACs to use on its own).
This makes good sense for the devtest story and makes testing
w/ VMs more sensible.

When using TOCI w/ real bare metal (using a predined set of MAC
addresses and power management commands) we make the following
assumptions:

 1) when setting up the seed VM we assign the first MAC in the list

 2) when setting up the undercloud we skip the first MAC and assign
   all the others.

** This should work well and allow us to bring up a single undercloud
node and possibly a multi-node overcloud as well.

This patch also includes updates to pass in parameters to
setup-baremetal instead of relying on environment variables for
everything.

Lastly, this change also gets rid of some TOCI logic to handle
using real bare metal nodes (using power management commands etc).
Now that we have support in incubator/register-nodes for power
management we can just use that instead.

Change-Id: I112c4a18c8e9d6e8ad5f152305ff018e79e97ecc

commit_message:
Updates to work with latest setup-baremetal cmds.

TOCI updates to work with the latest triple-incubator
scripts.

Recently we changed setup-baremetal and register-nodes in
the incubator so that the way it handles MACS works differently.
Specifically we now only pass the MAC addresses we want
register-nodes to actually use (previously that script contained
some rather janky logic to decide which MACs to use on its own).
This makes good sense for the devtest story and makes testing
w/ VMs more sensible.

When using TOCI w/ real bare metal (using a predined set of MAC
addresses and power management commands) we make the following
assumptions:

 1) when setting up the seed VM we assign the first MAC in the list

 2) when setting up the undercloud we skip the first MAC and assign
   all the others.

** This should work well and allow us to bring up a single undercloud
node and possibly a multi-node overcloud as well.

This patch also includes updates to pass in parameters to
setup-baremetal instead of relying on environment variables for
everything.

Lastly, this change also gets rid of some TOCI logic to handle
using real bare metal nodes (using power management commands etc).
Now that we have support in incubator/register-nodes for power
management we can just use that instead.

Change-Id: I112c4a18c8e9d6e8ad5f152305ff018e79e97ecc

commit_message:
Align build files and requirements

This is not an actual python project, so there is an amount of cruft
in the repo that is not needed. However, it does generate tarballs in
OpenStack Infra, so it needs the tox venv environment and the pbr
setup.py stuff. It also is totally possible to check python files in
the repo for flake8 violations, so set that up.

Change-Id: Ifb94f65912716efe1c4596d552beee92d2dc3d6a

commit_message:
Workaround Neutron DHCP scheduling failure.

For some reason the native Neutron PXE setup is failing to schedule
the DHCP agent to handle the ctlplane network. This fugly hack will
address it until we investigate the root cause.

Change-Id: Ieb4b6542ae9298ef395cf3afbf4161d50b7ab62c

I like everything except for motions dir. In a perfect world, I think that each motion is just a change in a set of content that is there already. So, a motion to add a new program would be just a commit that adds a program to a file. (with all of the things we've decided making up something similar to the charter, except it's not the charter)

That said - I'm not sure where the "OpenStack is One Project" or "projects will use tox" type decisions should go ... perhaps that's what the motions dir is for? So perhaps that's just a differently named dir?'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2013-09-04 07:47:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Monty: I see your point. I agree a lot of motions should ideally just result in a change in a reference document. That said, there are a number of formal votes we had in the past to state a point or stress the importance of something. There could be one day votes where the TC is called to resolve a dispute between projects. We need to be able to vote and record that outcome as well. Think like UN resolutions.

So "motions" is probably not the right name for that directory (as there will be motions without a motions/* document). commit_message:
Initial structure and reference documents

Create initial repository structure and add the following
reference documents:

- charter: The authoritative copy of the TC charter (copied from wiki)
- members: Current TC members with election expiration
- programs.yaml: List of official programs including PTLs, codenames,
  mission statements...
- extra-atcs: List of people being granted an ATC exception

Change-Id: Ia2df3bf0808af8cfa306092442160d5ecb14dfb0

'}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2013-09-26 12:35:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

Hmmmm, I think this change will interfere with some of the partition coordination logic around managing deleted and newly created alarms.

For example, suppose a bunch of alarms are all disabled temporarily. The coordinator will track these as deleted alarms (since they drop out of the alarms list due to the new query constraint), and possibly initiate a re-balance if there are enough of them.

When/if the disabled alarms are re-enabled, these will be treated as newly created alarms and assigned to a partition (not necessarily a problem).

However I'm not sure that re-balance is necessary, if we take the assumption that disabled alarms are likely to be re-enabled in the future.

How about instead allowing the master's main query to remain unconstrained, but then account for the enabled status in the _distribute method?

i.e. add:

  alarms = [a for a in alarms if a.enabled]

before the line that calculates the per_evaluator allocation?

Previously allocated alarms that are subsequently disabled would stay allocated under both approaches I think until a rebalance occurs, so the alarm service would still have to check the enabled field and ignore as appropriate.

However allowing disabled alarms to remain allocated should be fine from an equity perspective as long as disabled alarms are essentially randomly distributed.

Cheers,
Eoghan"}, {'account_id': 2813, 'date': '2013-09-26 16:09:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: (2 inline comments)

Currently ceilometerclient.alarms.list() return only enabled alarms. (without https://review.openstack.org/#/c/48418/), So the rebalance already occur when user disable a bunch of alarm. This is why I have kept this behavior.

But that make sense to calculate partitions with all alarms. 

I guess you suggestion have a issue, because if a user enable a disabled alarm, _master_role() will never call _distribute(), so the newly enabled alarm will never assigned to a partition.



What do you think about just filtering in assigned_alarms() only.

So the balance are done with all alarms, each partition have enabled and disabled alarms assigned but the evaluation is done only on enabled alarm.

This permit to evaluate re-enabled alarm without waiting rebalance or re-assign.

I think that make sense because you must have sized your infra to evaluate all created alarms, no ?

My next changeset will have this proposition.'}, {'account_id': 2813, 'date': '2013-09-26 16:11:02.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2013-09-26 18:22:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

Yes, of course, I'd forgotten about the disabled alarms being inadvertently excluded from the list query issued by the master. The approach in the latest version of patch makes sense.

Thanks,
Eoghan"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-26 19:28:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

commit_message:
Don't load into alarms evaluators disabled alarms

With this patch, alarm evaluators query the ceilometer API with only
enabled alarms inteads of loading all alarms and skip the disabled one.

Related to bug #1231328

Change-Id: I7121c1d2703f2f82a7d910431696aa31cbf7fbe6

commit_message:
Allow to get a disabled alarm

This change allow to get a disabled alarm.

To do this, it:
* add the ability to query the alarm-list API with the 'enabled' fields.
* change the default visibility of alarm-list API from enabled only to all.

Fixes bug #1231328

Change-Id: I80cd691696f7630d2ac9e9b2a69b5b0ae5ee7968

commit_message:
Fix XML serializer for QoS Specs extension

This patch fixes XML serializer for QoS Specs exension calls like
list(), show(), associations().  Note that using XML as input for
create(), update() doesn't support yet.

Closes-Bug: # 1229619

Change-Id: I2eab9d69e05bb03269b51731458994d6268ac852

commit_message:
Pass new undercloud-vm parameter for native PXE.

Neutron native PXE requires a config setting to be enabled in
nova.conf, but until we have a split out undercloud template, it's
controlled via yet another parameter.

Change-Id: I1e8957b3af1d502eefcba961197f0f36eaa25708

commit_message:
Fix submitting hive job

 * Added hive xml schema version to workflow xml
 * Fix MySQL db accessing using hive user
 * Fix MySQL host in hive-site.xml
 * Generating password for hive MySQL user and set it to config

Change-Id: I40553bf80247a75e6d64295518916ee2c615117a

commit_message:
Create database from models for SQLite

Alembic does not support SQLite, and we don't recommend to use SQLite
in production deployments, so migrations are rarely needed for SQLite.
So we don't bother about working around SQLite limitations, and create
database from models when it is in use. Of course, we still use
alembic to migrate schema on 'real' databases.

Change-Id: I8237a29c7bf5b60136bb1b72fd029fe9ce1abe1f

commit_message:
Fix to enable delete of firewall in PENDING_CREATE state

Firewall will in PENDING_CREATE state if there is no underlying router in the
tenant. When the router and an associated i/f is created then with a sequence
of msgs it is set to ACTIVE state by the plugin. If a delete is triggered when
in PENDING_CREATE state in such a situation, the msg was ignored - fixing this to
account for the fact that a delete makes sense in this situation so the agent
sends the appropriate msg back to the plugin so it can delete it.

Change-Id: Id1db0a8413fd815b518fe4dc57fc6277c09e7f00
Closes-Bug: #1223478

commit_message:
Reverse the order of interface update and DNAT rule config

Configure DNAT rule first before adding floating ip address to interface
so advanced service router will not receive packets by accident before
DNAT rule configured.

Verified that traffic goes to the VM the created floating ip associated
with right after config.

Change-Id: I415d1138511f41c209f1f2a9c2f12c2cfd3d16f0
Closes-Bug: #1229548

commit_message:
Retrieve security group quotas from Neutron if enabled

Secuirty group quota information in Project overview charts,
Admin defaults panel, and Admin create/update project is
retrieved from Neutron secuirty group is enabled.

Neutron security group is enbled when Neutron is used Neutron
security group extension is supported by a backend plugin.

Also removes the logic to remove quotas of floating IP and fixed IP
when neutron is enabled in dashboards/admin/defaults/tabs.py.
quotas.get_default_quota_data() already handles it properly
and this logic is no longer required.

Closes-Bug: #1212600

Change-Id: I59f069931fad519ca4ec135b92df0040ec8fc230

Sorry, I'm going to have to -2 this. The reason behind not exporting, which I utterly failed at documenting, was that disk-image-builder and potentially other things capture variables and log them, and we really don't want that happening to arbitrary credentials.

write-tripleorc can query heat if you need to recover credentials that were passed into heat (currently most of them except demo I believe). And you can reset the demo password via keystone.

HTH,
Rob"}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-09-30 06:03:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

commit_message:
Export generated passwords.

Not sure if these were intentionally not exported before or not.  But,
I think they need to be saved somehow.  Exporting will allow them to
be saved by the write-tripleorc script (seperate commit), which is
only run on demand.

Change-Id: Ied849e6332178e6ab6f800356d021b68b0cae666

[{'created': '2013-09-17 00:04:44.000000000', 'message': "Database migration cleanup I - Alembic translation

This is the first in a series of patches to clean up the database
migrations in Ceilometer for the final Havana release. We plan to
move fully to Alembic in the first Icehouse milestone, but having
both Alembic and SA-migrate in the same codebase has been
confusing and caused a number of problems -- not the least of
which is that the Alembic migrations have not been tested in the
unit test gates.

This first patch does not remove the Alembic migrations. Rather, it
adds a single SA-migrate migration (016_alembic_translation) that
applies all of the migrations that were in the four Alembic migrations
as a single SA-migrate migration and then removes the alembic_version
database table.

The new migration does NOT support SQLite and so does not get run
by the **current** unit test case base class for the SQLAlchemy
storage driver (which simply calls migration.upgrade() on each test
case run on the SQLite database used in unittests). However, there
are gate tests that exercise all of the MySQL and PostgreSQL
SA-migrate migrations, so problems with the migration file should be
caught by those tests.

The next phase in this series will be the removal of Alembic from the
Ceilometer codebase for the final Havana release.

At the start of Icehouse, we'll essentially do an initial Alembic
migration that starts off from where Havana's SA-migrate-controlled
schema left off and remove SA-migrate from Ceilometer, going forward
only with Alembic. For stable/havana Ceilometer, contributors will
still need to submit SA-migrate migrations IFF their code changes the
database schema -- which being a stable branch should not happen except
in extreme circumstances.

Reference mailing list conversations here:

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2013-September/014593.html

Change-Id: I1d6d5f601bdf03f43cb7e14768321120598d784c

commit_message:
Database migration cleanup I - Alembic translation

This is the first in a series of patches to clean up the database
migrations in Ceilometer for the final Havana release. We plan to
move fully to Alembic in the first Icehouse milestone, but having
both Alembic and SA-migrate in the same codebase has been
confusing and caused a number of problems -- not the least of
which is that the Alembic migrations have not been tested in the
unit test gates.

This first patch does not remove the Alembic migrations. Rather, it
adds a single SA-migrate migration (016_alembic_translation) that
applies all of the migrations that were in the four Alembic migrations
as a single SA-migrate migration and then removes the alembic_version
database table.

The new migration does NOT support SQLite and so does not get run
by the **current** unit test case base class for the SQLAlchemy
storage driver (which simply calls migration.upgrade() on each test
case run on the SQLite database used in unittests). However, there
are gate tests that exercise all of the MySQL and PostgreSQL
SA-migrate migrations, so problems with the migration file should be
caught by those tests.

The next phase in this series will be the removal of Alembic from the
Ceilometer codebase for the final Havana release.

At the start of Icehouse, we'll essentially do an initial Alembic
migration that starts off from where Havana's SA-migrate-controlled
schema left off and remove SA-migrate from Ceilometer, going forward
only with Alembic. For stable/havana Ceilometer, contributors will
still need to submit SA-migrate migrations IFF their code changes the
database schema -- which being a stable branch should not happen except
in extreme circumstances.

Reference mailing list conversations here:

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2013-September/014593.html

Change-Id: I1d6d5f601bdf03f43cb7e14768321120598d784c

commit_message:
Fix error handling when login to a storage target fails

When login to a storage target fails with Hyper-V, an
UnboundLocalError gets thrown due to the target_iqn variable
having not yet been defined.  This change updates the error
handling to log out of the storage target only if the login
succeeded.

Fixes Bug #1211774

Change-Id: I1d041a7c6ca90ca41b5af098451e7dfc99a97e1f

commit_message:
remove multi_host check for dhcp checksum

Fixes 1219637

This removes the conditional check that actives the workaround
for adding dhcp checksums so that dhcp will work with older clients.
This check is necessary for single host configurations as well as
multi host once as some single code configurations (such as devstack)
will have multiple VM's on one machine with a local dhcp server.

This workaround will save a lot of headache with devstack since without
devstack may mysteriously refuse to work because of dhcp problems.

Change-Id: I25019520a57e650ce010713f85e9b64965fcb5bc

Seems we may be failing target create silently,
the situation appears to be that the actual device
lun is not created.  This has been appearing in the
gates on create from snapshot.

This change adds some logging that will help us determine
if it's the actual create, or if it's the attempted update
while the dd process is possibly holding the volume in a busy
state causing the target update to add lun 1 to fail.

Change-Id: If5d4219dedae4649982fa9c13f131bf5f38fb7c4

commit_message:
Add debug logging for targets

Seems we may be failing target create silently,
the situation appears to be that the actual device
lun is not created.  This has been appearing in the
gates on create from snapshot.

This change adds some logging that will help us determine
if it's the actual create, or if it's the attempted update
while the dd process is possibly holding the volume in a busy
state causing the target update to add lun 1 to fail.

Change-Id: If5d4219dedae4649982fa9c13f131bf5f38fb7c4

commit_message:
Add error logs for Huawei driver

Log some errors to avoid losing the exception messages.
HVS driver do repeated judgements for JSON results, here add error
logs and replace these judgement codes with a assertion function.

fixes bug 1229877
Change-Id: Icd1e859566e07c0f02aa0b2d5c136a2048524527

VMware: Fixes ignoring multi host scan issue

Fixes a careless programming error leading to scanning only 1 ESX host
under the vCenter server for datastores.

Fixes bug: 1229654

[{'created': '2013-09-25 19:57:45.000000000', 'message': 'Allow upgrade from Grizzly with ThinLVMVolumeDriver

In Grizzly, LVM thin provisioning was used by setting
volume_driver=...ThinLVMVolumeDriver.  In Havana this
functionality has moved under the standard LVM driver
with the option "lvm_type=thin" used to enable it.

We should account for the old volume_driver class path
so that the volume service behaves as expected for users
upgrading from Grizzly ThinLVM configurations.

Closes-Bug: #1231116
Change-Id: Ic29f0e5c1036232078af5c6d83c61c75a35cccd4
'}]
commit_message:
Allow upgrade from Grizzly with ThinLVMVolumeDriver

In Grizzly, LVM thin provisioning was used by setting
volume_driver=...ThinLVMVolumeDriver.  In Havana this
functionality has moved under the standard LVM driver
with the option "lvm_type=thin" used to enable it.

We should account for the old volume_driver class path
so that the volume service behaves as expected for users
upgrading from Grizzly ThinLVM configurations.

Closes-Bug: #1231116
Change-Id: Ic29f0e5c1036232078af5c6d83c61c75a35cccd4

This changeset only copies the v2 files into the appropriate v3
directories unchanged. This is being tried in order to make
reviewing of the porting easier as gerrit will display only what
is actually changed for v3 rather than entirely new files.

port test_flavors into v3 part2

this ports test_flavors into v3 and

Adds the IpAddressGenerationFailureClient exception so
a more specific exception than NeutronClientException is raised
when IPs run out. This will allow for better exception

commit_message:
Adds IpAddressGenerationFailureClient exception

Adds the IpAddressGenerationFailureClient exception so
a more specific exception than NeutronClientException is raised
when IPs run out. This will allow for better exception
handling in Nova and help fix nova bug 1212137

Change-Id: I921ba5d5f5ee3dc9620dcdbbd04d6fef824c9a53
Closes-Bug: 1231836

[{'created': '2013-09-19 19:08:53.000000000', 'message': 'Fix type change in bootable setting of volume view

Change Idd47a0a8069ee905b81c7aae562b82767ad91930 fixed a db
query issue, by removing the image_metadata querie in the get/show
methods.

The problem however is that we just passed the setting from the volume
object directly in the summary view builder.  This results in changing
the type of the value from a string "true/false" to a bool True/False
which is no good.

This patch converts the object member back to a string like it used to
be so we don't break any compat or expectations in API behavior.

Fixes bug #1227837

Change-Id: I55c0e25134ae429802ddf313d6d26f1fad19ca94
'}]
commit_message:
Fix type change in bootable setting of volume view

Change Idd47a0a8069ee905b81c7aae562b82767ad91930 fixed a db
query issue, by removing the image_metadata querie in the get/show
methods.

The problem however is that we just passed the setting from the volume
object directly in the summary view builder.  This results in changing
the type of the value from a string "true/false" to a bool True/False
which is no good.

This patch converts the object member back to a string like it used to
be so we don't break any compat or expectations in API behavior.

Fixes bug #1227837

Change-Id: I55c0e25134ae429802ddf313d6d26f1fad19ca94

commit_message:
Make it possible to enable native neutron PXE.

This is used to control the dhcp_options_enabled flag in nova.conf,
needed to enable PXE orchestration (until Nova assumes all Neutron
libraries and servers support it).

Change-Id: I035a2341d829a9987eeeebdd9c22f039e69489db

commit_message:
Change stack-list to not deserialize data

    Stack-list is one of heat's slowest operations.
    It uses the orm to fetch resources for every stack
    in the database, then spends a lot of time deserializing
    resource data. This patch forces resources and dependencies
    do be lazily loaded. Switching to WIP.

    bug 1214602

    Change-Id: Ieec481cb8ab211054f8956090ad97a687c9a616b

Change-Id: Ib950f3ab6e27fdaeb878b61788686e2800c70892

    resource data. This patch forces resources and dependencies

commit_message:
Conform stack resource error so it gives a 4xx

This exception was added and landed while the change to use
RequestLimitExceeded was still in progress. Giving a 5xx error when the
user has caused the problem directly is not what we want.

We leave the exception in place to allow the shared error message. I
also have hopes that we will be o-k with extra exceptions and just
extend RequestLimitExceeded when we have a similar situation.

Change-Id: Ic9b176625e6ad2b8c42c420dab79984d134304e5

commit_message:
Ensure server is in ACTIVE state

ImagesOneServerTestJSON's setUpClass has code for deploy. However there
is no setUp method that ensures the server is ACTIVE, so Copy code from
ServerActionsTestJSON where setUp() which ensures that one is available.

Partial-Bug: #1218391

Change-Id: Iff74fd69e1779b66aeb76f1c0716893cc10c4dcb

commit_message:
Ensure that security group agent is bound prior to accessing

When the Neutron agents start and the security group agent callbacks
are not registered there may be exceptions.

Fixes bug: #1232758

Change-Id: I4c1ff96b8acfcee4c84a73c9400040c96f8418a9

commit_message:
Differentiate between repo and module name

Project/repo names often have -'s in them, which is evil in python
module land.

Change-Id: Ife1f57a6c7ebdd218340e2a631222d471dec5e2b

commit_message:
Fix live LDAP tests

The live LDAP tests were failing. The tests for case
sensitivity for project name and user name failed because the
attribute is not case sensitive. The test for updating a
missing attribute with a falsy value was failing because the
attribute chosen for the project description does not allow an
empty string.

Change-Id: I723c40b5eab24ac13e27fd040d0d881998f106db
Related-Bug: #1231772

the attrlist from causing an exception when trying to iterate on
the None singleton.

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-09-25 06:49:56.000000000', 'message': "Update user_attribute_ignore for LDAP Identity config

With a recent patch to keystone, the use of tenantId, tenant_id, and
default_project_id was normalized to reference default_project_id for
all cases internally and translate to the expected results at the
controller (v2.0 returns tenantId, v3 returns default_project_id).

Devstack must now properly ignore the expected mapped LDAP attribute
of 'default_project_id' instead of the old 'tenantId'.  Without this
fix devstack will fail when using the LDAP identity backend because
the 'default_project_id' has been made a special case that requires
the operator of a Openstack cloud to explicitly choose an attribute
to map 'default_project_id' to if storing that value is desired.
Without explicitly mapping that attribute and not having it in the
'user_attribute_ignore' config option, the user_creates can fail.

related-bug: 1219739
Change-Id: I1dd3719de50f6d0948b3a9743e32a03d0ac56b3c
"}]
commit_message:
Update user_attribute_ignore for LDAP Identity config

With a recent patch to keystone, the use of tenantId, tenant_id, and
default_project_id was normalized to reference default_project_id for
all cases internally and translate to the expected results at the
controller (v2.0 returns tenantId, v3 returns default_project_id).

Devstack must now properly ignore the expected mapped LDAP attribute
of 'default_project_id' instead of the old 'tenantId'.  Without this
fix devstack will fail when using the LDAP identity backend because
the 'default_project_id' has been made a special case that requires
the operator of a Openstack cloud to explicitly choose an attribute
to map 'default_project_id' to if storing that value is desired.
Without explicitly mapping that attribute and not having it in the
'user_attribute_ignore' config option, the user_creates can fail.

related-bug: 1219739
Change-Id: I1dd3719de50f6d0948b3a9743e32a03d0ac56b3c

'}, {'account_id': 1689, 'date': '2013-09-27 18:23:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(2 inline comments)

Looks pretty good so far, but I'd like to see a bit more robustness around assumptions/limitations of the driver. I understand that the mechanism driver only handles VLAN networks and only deals with a single network connection right now. But I don't think that precludes users from creating other network types or using multiple physical networks within the same deployment. For example, GRE or VXLAN might be used for tenant networks, or a flat provider network might be used on the same or a different physical network. 

I think some simple checks of the bound network_type and physical_network values would address these situations by having the driver ignore everything except VLANs on one specific physical network. See my in-line comments."}, {'account_id': 6694, 'date': '2013-09-27 20:22:43.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 1689, 'date': '2013-09-27 20:33:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Looks like most of the comments have been addressed. My only remaining concern that this point is that there is no way to use this mechanism driver in an environment where more than one physical network is being used. Would you consider defining a managed_physical_network config variable, and if it is set, ignoring all VLAN networks that don't match it?"}, {'account_id': 6694, 'date': '2013-09-27 20:52:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Robert Kurkurai
Are you suggesting that in ml2_conf_cisco.ini a new variable called 'managed_physical_network' is created. And as an example a customer sets that variable to physnet1 and then compares that against the ml2_conf.ini value [ml2_type_vlan] network_vlan_ranges "physical network name" and only take actions for the physnet1?

if yes, do you want me to try and get that in today?
I believe RC1 deadline is today.'}, {'account_id': 1689, 'date': '2013-09-27 21:00:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Rich,

Yes, that sounds like the kind of scenario I have in mind. A different physical_network, physnet2, might be used as a VLAN provider external network, and should be ignored.

I think the code change would be very simple. Just add the config variable, and have _get_vlanid() return None if the managed_physical_network is set and doesn't match the binding's physical_network. This would ignore "unmanaged" networks in the same way it ignores network_types other than vlan.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-27 21:30:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

commit_message:
ML2 Cisco Nexus mech driver portbinding support

This commit adds portbinding extension support to
the cisco nexus mechanism driver.

Fixes bug: 1220878

Change-Id: I72003961b46190b82681b471f4f9cb5b11d3d068

commit_message:
Removes pre_live_migration need for Fixed IPs

This commit removes the validation that requires Fixed IP Addresses
for pre_live_migration.  The original comment regarding the
pre_live_migration requiring Fixed IP Addresses alluded to uncertainty
about it not being required.  Workloads should not require a Fixed IP
Address for migration, typically just the storage is required to be
similar.

The commit also updates the associated test case to ensure that no
exception is thrown in the pre_live_migration if a fixed IP Address
is not specified.

Change-Id: I2c4d4dae2cb0f00c67f0f731b5080196564b37da
Closes-Bug: #1226226

commit_message:
skip test_run_stop_terminate_instance

This test case leads to frequent recheck on the neutron gate,
both at instance creation and instance deletion wait.

This is the simplest ec2 instance test, ec2 api does not do anything
special what the nova does not. It is also very strange just only this
test case causes issues.

Looks like soma state information is different on the services.

Related Bug #1223161

Change-Id: Ic5b88fb321b1c389280d0ce15de8842a24be9e1a

commit_message:
Correctly set the L3 service plugin for ML2

ML2 uses a service plugin for L3. This patch to devstack
correctly sets this by setting or updating the variable
Q_SERVICE_PLUGIN_CLASSES, which makes ML2 compatible when
running with other service plugins (e.g. LBaaS and VPN).

Fixes bug 1231622

Change-Id: I0ce1f5a42bd052995135ffac1ee5ef382d69789e

Normalise RECLONE flag to True Or False.

RECLONE flag now uses function trueorfalse for flag handling.

commit_message:
Expose all versions of Ironic API

In the observable future new versions of the Ironic
API will appear. That's why it's reasonable to expose
the endpoint that will provide access to all versions
of the API.

Closes-Bug: #1229780
Change-Id: I4ec2b45688da3fa6c0d43e8be60885774cfbffd6

commit_message:
Remove deprecated task states

Task states STARTING and STOPPING were replaced with POWERING_ON and
POWERING_OFF in Grizzly and can now be removed.

'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2013-08-21 18:08:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Do not merge

I don't know what mageia is (oh, a Mandriva fork). Please convince me that adding it is worth the effort as it will not be supported by any of the core devs and will potentially be broken by the next patch that comes along.  This is the first I've heard of the need for it so some demonstration of a community of support would be good."}, {'account_id': 8375, 'date': '2013-08-23 14:16:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

This is part of an effort to make Mageia a major distribution for computational astrophysics.  The first step is to have openstack and devstack run cleanly on the next release of Mageia, and then combine this with some of the astrophysical tools that have been added.  To do this, we've made a number of bug fixes and enhancements to supermin and libvirt, and I've submitted a talk to the Hong Kong conference about everything we've had to do to get openstack to work.

It's possible for us to keep the patches on a separate tree, but I think that adds more work for everyone."}, {'account_id': 7623, 'date': '2013-08-26 07:56:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Dear Dean,

I'm pretty surprised of your reaction. You don't know Mageia but please consider the following point.

- Mageia is not Mandriva
We did fork Mandriva because of some bad strategic decisions taken by them. Since 3 Years we are making our own at 100%.

- Mageia is a 100% community distribution
As we can look here (https://wiki.mageia.org/en/Org), we are running as a community. After 3 successful releases, I can say that it this model works well.

- Mageia is more popular than you thought

That's not an absolute meaning but on the last 12 month we are number 2 on DistroWatch.

Linux.com listed us as the one of the 5 most important project of 2012 : http://www.linux.com/learn/docs/682469-the-5-most-important-linux-projects-of-2012

- Mageia is not only a Distro for Desktops
Mageia is not designed for being a distro for desktop even if it's nice to run this way.  Really, we are working hard to have a good product that people like. 

- Magiea is friendly with upstream
Openstack is a strong demand this days and we want to satisfy it. We aim at being friendly with upstream projects and that's why Joseph came to you to add Mageia in Openstack. We don't aim at keeping the work for us and apply patches just for the fun. If we had to add some in our packages, upstream team would be informed to discuss it and integrate it if it worth.

Please approve this addition, that would help us to grow and continue our way to get a nice community distribution.

Regards,
Erwan"}, {'account_id': 8375, 'date': '2013-08-31 18:53:38.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2013-08-31 18:53:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Automatically re-added by Gerrit trivial rebase detection script.'}, {'account_id': 8375, 'date': '2013-08-31 19:06:52.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 8375, 'date': '2013-08-31 19:11:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

FYI, I'm going to keep this thread updated with the latest patch sets which will track devstack changes and have bug fixes.

I'm hoping that if I can keep this going for a while, it will show that Mageia is serious about tracking openstack changes."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-31 19:34:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Works for me

commit_message:
Define a way to load storage back-ends

With this patch, those who load their own back-ends should be able
to stop overriding private methods of AccountController and
ContainerController. However, the testing was not exhaustive just yet.
We only made sure that we're not breaking the existing Swift.

Note that this commit inserts a common way to load DiskFile and
DB broker classes in every place they are used. This is actually
a fiction at present, because additional dependencies on the on-disk
layout exist due to assumptions in auditors and replicators.
We do it purely for uniformity.

This version disposes with confusing and misleading names, such as
"lfs" and "group", and is configured in one place, swift.conf, for
all servers and daemons.

Change-Id: I2aaea02f98a27be1225a06ce60336c13ba62993b

I have changed my mind, I agree with Joshua.  Even though this patch is trivial enough its not worth making an exception to the rule of not changing migrations once they land in trunk.'}, {'account_id': 100, 'date': '2013-09-25 19:19:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I'll defend merging this.

We don't have a rule of making migrations immutable. We have a rule of making the functionality of migrations immutable.

Other migrations have had changes for a variety of reasons:
- _ was no longer monkey patched, necessitating a new import added
- fix bugs causing testing problems
- change copyright headers
- remove unused code (creating logger, imports, etc)
- fix bugs causing the migrations to fail to function (on PostgreSQL, downgrade bugs, etc)
- style changes (removing use of locals(), whitespace, etc)
- make migrations faster
- add comments to clarify code
- improve compatibility with newer versions of SQLAlchemy

It's a mistake to make migrations immutable to any changes. Even making migrations immutable to functional changes is a bit of a grey area considering how many bugs have been fixed, or code rewritten for performance reasons. Obviously retroactively changing a migration to add a new column should not happen.

That said, I think an argument could be made that this change shouldn't be merged during a feature freeze since it's just a cleanup. I still think it should get merged at some point."}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-09-25 21:49:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Johannes, I agree there are many exceptions to the rule of not changing migrations once they land in trunk.  And this is potentially a good one.  But considering how minor the change is and feature freeze I think we should at least wait.

The patch does look very simple and would be surprised if it will cause any new bugs, but during Feature Freeze I want to err on the side of caution especially for migrations.

That being said dropping my -2."}, {'account_id': 4458, 'date': '2013-09-29 05:46:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Continue to use implicit nullable=True in sqlalchemy

Change-Id I22fe2d0caca77005553a6a6f0c7cc2d3e8ea5512 removed some nullable=True
statements because in sqlalchemy nullable is set to True by default.

In migrations, there are some column definitions telling nullable=True, which
is not necessary, so this patch is to remove them.

Change-Id: Ice6bb74ffbc518a948d0e06ba150289b2106df05
Signed-off-by: Shane Wang <shane.wang@intel.com>

commit_message:
Add error log for SystemExit in l3-agent

The SystemExit exception should be logged in l3-agent, the
operator may miss the useful exception messages to debug.

    * Add error log for SystemExit in l3-agent.
    * Add unit test for None and Wrong interface_driver.

Closes-Bug #1229105

Change-Id: I9ac60a528c1e88827078d552a30c8d571066d21c

[{'created': '2013-09-27 22:58:20.000000000', 'message': "Fix auto-deletion of ports and subnets in ML2

When a network is deleted, certain ports and any subnets referencing
it are auto-deleted. The implementation of
NeutronDBPluginV2.delete_network() does this at the DB level, so ML2's
mechanism drivers were not being called.

Ml2Plugin.delete_network() is changed to not use the base class's
method, and to auto-delete ports and subnets by calling its own
delete_port() and delete_subnet() methods outside of the
transaction. A loop avoids race conditions with ports or subnets being
asynchronously added to the network.

Closes-Bug: 1230330
Change-Id: Icf21400c9938eec29d70da8497b9ef92642131e2
"}]
commit_message:
Fix auto-deletion of ports and subnets in ML2

When a network is deleted, certain ports and any subnets referencing
it are auto-deleted. The implementation of
NeutronDBPluginV2.delete_network() does this at the DB level, so ML2's
mechanism drivers were not being called.

Ml2Plugin.delete_network() is changed to not use the base class's
method, and to auto-delete ports and subnets by calling its own
delete_port() and delete_subnet() methods outside of the
transaction. A loop avoids race conditions with ports or subnets being
asynchronously added to the network.

Closes-Bug: 1230330
Change-Id: Icf21400c9938eec29d70da8497b9ef92642131e2

Fixes Hyper-V agent RPC calls for ML2 support

Adds support for the RPC report status in the Hyper-V
agent and plugin.

Fixes bug: #1226654

commit_message:
Use built-in print() instead of print statement

In python 3 print statement is not supported, so we should use
only print() functions.

Fixes bug 1226943

Change-Id: I6f55dafb8f272e503dac34f59a9731e992a5ceaa

The to_xml method of libvirt driver will generate xml file of instance
during hard reboot/spawn/rescue/migrate and other operations, and the
image_meta is used for generating correct xml of instance.
But the accurate image_meta may not be passed into the get_guest_config,
so some configs related to the image_meta will be lost, we need to get the
image metadata if it is not passed to the to_xml method.

Fixes bug 1206809

commit_message:
Get image metadata in to_xml for generating xml

The to_xml method of libvirt driver will generate xml file of instance
during hard reboot/spawn/rescue/migrate and other operations, and the
image_meta is used for generating correct xml of instance.
But the accurate image_meta may not be passed into the get_guest_config,
so some configs related to the image_meta will be lost, we need to get the
image metadata if it is not passed to the to_xml method.

Fixes bug 1206809
Change-Id: I6942837905334a652cda64d7dd41d3b575846d93

<atiwari> mtreinish, regarding https://review.openstack.org/#/c/46341/, I am not disabling the test just modified it so that it would not failed with new response code

<atiwari> wd that be OK?
<mtreinish> atiwari: that's not valid if you're making a change to a publish api we have a policy on getting that merged
<mtreinish> the commit making the change has to have a +2 from a core on the project
<mtreinish> then we merge the change to skip it with a bug to track the change
<mtreinish> you merge the commit
<mtreinish> and then unskip the test making the api change to the test
<mtreinish> I forget where we have that published but here is a presentation that gives a basic outline for it: http://dague.net/presentations/tempest-101/#/10
<atiwari> I am totally lost, you want us to merge the https://review.openstack.org/#/c/46123 for which I am making the change in thsi test?

* SergeyLukjanov has quit (Quit: Computer has gone to sleep.)

<atiwari> how come that will have +2, Jenkins will fail

commit_message:
Validate token calls return 404 on invalid tokens

Invalid X-Subject-Token was resulting in HTTP 401 rather than 404
This is causing the auth_token middleware to re-authenticate
It expects a 404 on an invalid token.

Change-Id: Ieb4cbd4f69b4f3c5944eebc262e694e831d1ca6d
Fixed-Bug: #1221889
Fixed-Bug: #1186059

commit_message:
Add a script to submit changes to all projects

The script is intended to be consumed by OpenStack Infra - but really
could be used by anybody if they want to patch-bomb.

Change-Id: Ia881b2b2eb725d81b1e1dd087f1de235eb9f5962

commit_message:
Fix console db can't load attribute pool

Lists consoles failed when populate console_type from console
db's pool attribute. The reason was db api console_get_all_by_instance
didn't join with pool. So add param 'columns_to_join' for db api, and
join pool attribute when lists consoles.

Change-Id: I18b44860270a401c55cf02b4334b973fbf357b03
Closes-bug: #1223205

commit_message:
Avoid having twice Appendix A

Both user-guide and user-guide-admin had two versions appendices
labelled "A". The problem was setting appendixAutolabel to 1 in
the pom.xml file and manual overrides of the number in the files.
The patch cleanes all of this up and renames ch_resources.xml
to an appendix part.

security-guide and training-guide also set this variable but did
not have an appendix yet, so remove the variable there as well.

Change-Id: I446f4968b675d3286f2302071ddfa8037425fd6f

commit_message:
Move and refactor ImmutableMixin & EnumMixin to rally.utils

First of all these two mixins will be used not only for rally.consts
So move it to rally.utils

Improve ImmutableMixin, to be able to set parameters in __init__() method

Relax EnumMixin consts type, were supported only string values

Add tests for ImnutableMixin and EnumMixin

Change-Id: I52a0d3810c62855024bc3da34db1134e8ebde149

commit_message:
Remove Neutron VPN resources id attributes

This patch removes the id attributes from the various Neutron VPN
resources, as people should use Ref.

Change-Id: Idf81d109b930b246791a0f3c22bc04ce5054b939
Closes-Bug: #1230228

commit_message:
Revert "Enable q-vpn service"

This reverts commit abebbd61eb4758ca5cbab35f3494e7f0262e5bf9.

From the discussion in bug #1230407, the neutron deadlocks may be
a persistent latent issue with driving large amounts of rpc traffic
in neutron. The reason this became an issue this week may be related
to turning on q-vpn in the gate, as that generates even more traffic.

If we revert this change, and things go back to "normal" failure
rates, then this gives us more evidence in that direction.

Change-Id: Ia62dc1cd7efce3aaab5b8825e26082d42f629f88
Related-Bug: 1230407
