commit_message:
Install libffi-dev in SAIO docs.

If you don't, then newer versions of xattr won't install, and since
our xattr requirement is simply ">= 0.4" in requirements.txt, this
affects anyone setting up a new SAIO.

This happened with xattr 0.7, which was released on 2013-07-19.

Change-Id: Iaf335fa25a2908953d1fd218158ebedf5d01cc27

commit_message:
_get_tenant_by_name doesn't return correctly

If tempest_client is unset, _get_tenant_by_name will
definitely raise an exception, which is incorrect.

Change-Id: Id3e452a35d4f6c7083562689f556cac05868af45
Closes-Bug: #1231645

commit_message:
fix(wsgi): Validation exception strings not written for end users

When input validation fails, the validator raises an exception,
and the WSGI transport may returns the exception string
directly in the body of the error response.

This patch edits the validation exception strings to make them
read more naturally, so that they are more likely to be
understood by end users.

Change-Id: Iad78660d725410d0d9bc05852dca01b3cb3915c6

commit_message:
Provide config option to cap events per stack

Previously users could write to the events table infinitely. With this
change Heat will automatically prune some events if the maximum is
reached. The behavior can be disabled by setting max_events_per_stack to
zero.

Change-Id: I4fb2fefbd9bcd10ce1767ddf58a870206a6482a1
Fixes-Bug: #1209492

commit_message:
Handle case without session_persistence attr in LBaaS VIP

When no session persistence mechanism is used, session_persistence
attribute is not contained in a VIP dict returned from Neutron.
This commit add a logic to handle this case.

During the fix it turns out the current LBaaS Horizon support
does not consider a case of "No Session Persistence".
This commit fixes the following too:

* Display "None" in VIP detail (instead of "Type:" without a value)
* Add "No session persistence" choice to VIP creation workflow
  (Actually it replaces "Select session persistence" choice
   since "No session persistence" is the default value.)

This commit also fixes bugs related to LBaaS VIP:

* Add validation for Cookie Name for APP_COOKIE persistence
  in VIP update. (The same is done for VIP creation)
* Do not create a hyperlink if no VIP exist for a pool.

Change-Id: Icf2aa2454f5f6beb928368fb06823576bbe57f2f
Closes-Bug: #1231704

Add support for loadbalancer providers

Add provider column to pools table.
Add provider dropdown box to AddPool form.

Fixes bug 1226868

commit_message:
Only send gateway_ip on neutron subnet update when it's changed

Even if the gateway_ip is unchanged, neutron retruns error code
when the client trys to update gateway_ip which is already assigned.
In this fix, we will check gateway_ip is changed or not, then we send
the gateway_ip when it is changed.

Fixes bug 1227268
Change-Id: Ie6330a45a7998ffeb6a925be5bcc2c58ff9e6239

recheck no bug'}, {'account_id': 4458, 'date': '2013-08-22 06:11:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Probably using json will be better? We need to think more about a better solution for that. I also did some tests on sqla core. My test implementation is similar to yours. But I don't think that is not the best one. Also, you are actually constructing your own ORM instead of using sqla ORM.

Here is my test result and my thought which were sent to the mail list. FYI.

==========

We have 10K compute nodes in compute_nodes, and each node has 20 stat records.
As we know, by using sql-a ORM, it takes our test code 16 seconds to call compute_node_get_all() and get all nodes.
The return nodes are constructed a list of dictionaries, each dictionary has an attribute 'stats' to get the stats of the node by ORM.

I make a patch to replace ORM with sql-a APIs, and test it.
Calling compute_node_get_all() costs about 4 seconds. However the format of the return nodes is a little bit different from the above.
Without ORM, each node is represented by 20 records, which indicate 20 stat records after join.

Again, I have a patch to use MySQLdb instead of sqlalchemy to fetch all compute nodes. It takes about 2 seconds.
Certainly running the SQL query under mysql command costs 0.54 second.

I don't think using stat table as "key":"value" is a good idea, because each node should aggregate all stat records, translate them into real_name: real_value with statmap() after retrieving them from db, and translate them into key:value with _prep_stats_dict() before saving them to db, at least at this moment.
If we consider to remove ORM some day, the stat format of the query results should be a problem, or we need to construct 'stats' attribute for each node by ourselves based on those 20 records, which still costs time.

I agree with Chris to save 'stats' as a json at this moment, mentioned in the bug description. I have ever had a similar patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/38802/ which is abandoned currently.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-22 12:11:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

In response to the suggestion of some of the reviewers, I've conducted a series of experiments to measure peak python memory usage for different implementations of compute_node_get_all().

The memory usage has been measured via resource.getrusage(resource.RUSAGE_SELF).ru_maxrss.

Our implementation turns out to yield 5 times less memory usage than the old one.

Addressing the comment on the fetchall() method usage made by Roman Podolyaka: eliminating fetchall() calls yields ~103 MB memory usage, which is not a great improvement, so I've preferred to leave these calls to gain more time efficiency."}, {'account_id': 8507, 'date': '2013-08-28 10:43:32.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 9.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-28 12:08:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Works for me

[{'created': '2013-08-21 15:43:57.000000000', 'message': 'Safe Scheduler performance improvement

Scheduler stores the essential information for its work in DB in 3
tables: 'services', 'compute_nodes' and 'compute_node_stats'. For
each compute node, there is 1 record in 'services', 1 record in
'compute_nodes' and about 10 records in 'compute_node_stats'.

Each user request to scheduler to schedule an instance results
in a call to the db.compute_node_get_all() method which fetches
information about all compute nodes, their services and
corresponding stats in a single list.

There are 2 problems with the previous implementation of this
method. The first one was connected with network traffic: the
use of JOIN operation resulted in redundant informaion
returned from the DB in the resulting denormalized table. The
second one was a performance problem in the SQLAlchemy ORM's
implementation of data processing (slow model mappings in JOINs).

As we are returning all the data from these 3 tables, we
have implemented a lower-level approach to solve these problems:
to reduce the network traffic, the new implementation of this
method fetches all the necessary data from 3 tables separately,
queries only for those columns that will be actually needed by
the scheduler ('created_at', 'deleted_at', 'updated_at' and
'deleted' columns removed). It then joins these tables "by hand",
which allows to avoid using the slow SQLAlchemy ORM's model
mapping and thus enables to speed up the whole process
significantly.

We have tested the new implementation against the old one.
In our test example, we have 10k services, 10k compute_nodes and
100k records in the compute_node_stats (each key and each value is
15 characters in length) database. The results are as follows:

+-----------------------------------------------+-----------+---------+
| Approach                                      | Time      | Traffic |
+-----------------------------------------------+-----------+---------+
| sqla ORM joinedload (all columns)             | 15.58 sec | 26.8 MB |
+-----------------------------------------------+-----------+---------+
| sqla ORM joinedload (filtered columns)        | n/a       | 17.2 MB |
+-----------------------------------------------+-----------+---------+
| sqla core + join "by hand" (all columns)      | 7.67 sec  | 9.4 MB  |
+-----------------------------------------------+-----------+---------+
| sqla core + join "by hand" (filtered columns) | 5.15 sec  | 5.6 MB  |
+-----------------------------------------------+-----------+---------+

So our implementation has 3 times better performance and uses 5 times
less traffic.

commit_message:
Safe db.api.compute_node_get_all() performance improvement

Scheduler stores the essential information for its work in DB in 3
tables: 'services', 'compute_nodes' and 'compute_node_stats'. For
each compute node, there is 1 record in 'services', 1 record in
'compute_nodes' and about 10 records in 'compute_node_stats'.

Each user request to scheduler to schedule an instance results
in a call to the db.api.compute_node_get_all() method which fetches
the information about all the compute nodes, their services and
corresponding stats in a single list.

There were 2 problems with the previous implementation of this
method. The first one was connected with network traffic: the
use of JOIN operation resulted in redundant informaion
returned from the DB in the resulting denormalized table. The
second one was a performance problem in the SQLAlchemy ORM's
implementation of data processing (slow model mappings in JOINs).

As we are just returning all the data from these 3 tables, we
have implemented a lower-level approach to solve these problems:
to reduce the network traffic, the new implementation of this
method fetches all the necessary data from 3 tables separately,
querying only for those columns that will be actually needed by
the scheduler ('created_at', 'deleted_at', 'updated_at' and
'deleted' columns get removed if the 'no_date_fields' parameter is
set to True). It then joins these tables manually, which allows
to avoid using the slow SQLAlchemy ORM's model mapping and thus
enables to speed up the whole process significantly.

We have tested the new implementation against the old one (with
the 'no_date_fields' parameter set to True). In our test example,
we have 10k services, 10k compute_nodes and 100k records in the
compute_node_stats (each key and each value is 15 characters in
length) database. The results are as follows:

+---------------------------------------+-----------+---------+---------------+
| Approach                              | Time      | Traffic | Python memory |
+---------------------------------------+-----------+---------+---------------+
| ORM joinedload (all columns)          | 15.58 sec | 26.8 MB | 579.9 MB      |
+---------------------------------------+-----------+---------+---------------+
| ORM joinedload (filtered columns)     | n/a       | 17.2 MB | n/a           |
+---------------------------------------+-----------+---------+---------------+
| core + manual join (all columns)      | 7.67 sec  | 9.4 MB  | 223.6 MB      |
+---------------------------------------+-----------+---------+---------------+
| core + manual join (filtered columns) | 5.15 sec  | 5.6 MB  | 112.5 MB      |
+---------------------------------------+-----------+---------+---------------+

So our new implementation has 3 times better performance, uses 5 times
less traffic and yields 5 times less memory usage than the old one.

Test data was edited slightly here to reflect the real-world system
behaviour (services corresponding to compute nodes come with
binary='nova-compute').

Change-Id: Ie5ef00c974b810336787e88c78c93c15ca2890d3
Partial-Bug: #1212428

[{'created': '2013-09-27 09:52:23.000000000', 'message': 'Add "unshelve" command

The unshelve API, which starts the shelved vm instance, has been
implemented by Nova-server side.

commit_message:
Add "unshelve" command

The unshelve API, which starts the shelved vm instance, has been
implemented by Nova-server side.
This patch adds "unshelve" command for using the API.

Related-Bug: #1231827

Change-Id: Iae3208bfe896782b4e9af28346760511e75c2f4b

commit_message:
Add I18N related configurations

* Add Transifex config
* Add babel config to setup.cfg (extract_messages, compile_catalog)
* Add Babel to test-requirements.txt (It is only required
  when extracting and compiling catalogs
* Move English PO file to openstack_auth.pot
  (following other OpenStack projects)
* Remove English MO file

Change-Id: I7a908006c7a2c586d9d86cbfe3970b56f1461125

ch_overview.xml is now shared between user guides.

commit_message:
Add VPNaaS service support

VPNaaS is a new service in Neutron (Havana release).
This patchs aims to support default driver (OpenSwan) by installing
packages & configuring vpn_agent.ini.

implement blueprint vpnaas-support
Change-Id: I7f8a3fbc1b175eb0ea3a8868a04ea648c2b8f1b2
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-09-26 22:09:25.000000000', 'message': 'Protect oauth controller calls and update policy.json

We need to call controller.protected for most of the oauth_calls.
With the exception of the public ones (create_request_token,
create_access_token, and authenticate_access_token).
Also need to update the policy.json accordingly.

fixes bug 1231709

commit_message:
Protect oauth controller calls and update policy.json

We need to call controller.protected for most of the oauth_calls.
With the exception of the public ones (create_request_token,
create_access_token, and authenticate_access_token).
Also need to update the policy.json accordingly.

fixes bug 1231709

Change-Id: Ica111aa3ed82499d2de50d472754a0b5b3c5cc71

commit_message:
Add Neutron service_plugins support

In Havana, Neutron has now "service insertion" used
by some networking services as plugins.

This patchs aims to provide this new feature and also configure:
- FWaaS (Firewall)
- LBaaS (Load-Balancing)
- VPNaaS (Virtual Private Network)

implement blueprint fwaas-support
implement blueprint vpnaas-support

Change-Id: I07d85d8d1832af8bf9cb27346b3c096f5e5aa183
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>

commit_message:
Pin pecan to avoid the latest release

There is an issue with the latest Pecan release and WSME,
so pin to the previous release for now.

Works around bug 1232199

Change-Id: Ia616aece42689f84c0bec6bbb96a257f7321ba29

Historical note: < 0.8 was satisfied by 0.8 beta which broke things, hence this workaround with asymptotic condition <= 0.7.99.
Next time more 9s or fix pip version comparison (or is it a feature?)'}, {'account_id': 1955, 'date': '2013-09-17 11:53:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Should this be reverted to <=0.7.9999999 ?

SQLAlchemy==0.8.0b2 is still available from https://pypi.python.org/packages/source/S/SQLAlchemy/ and <0.8 picks it up: http://logs.openstack.org/55/45555/7/check/gate-keystone-python27/fac64cc/console.html.gz

and breaks sqlalchemy-migrate:

...lib/python2.7/site-packages/migrate/versioning/schema.py", line 10, in <module>
|     from sqlalchemy import exceptions as sa_exceptions
| ImportError: cannot import name exceptions'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2013-09-17 14:44:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

pip 1.4.1 should be "fixed" to not install beta releases by default'}, {'account_id': 1812, 'date': '2013-09-23 03:05:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Though if pip is configured to install beta versions then this technically breaks again.  Now I'm not pushing to revert this since we should be moving forward and just getting everything working with 0.8.x
Note sqlalchemy-migrate makes upgrade to 0.8.x awkward here.
Discussing that now on upstream mailing list:
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2013-September/015472.html"}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2013-09-28 11:30:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

this really shouldn't have landed, because we can't assume pip 1.4.1 for all systems."}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2013-09-08 02:18:41.000000000', 'message': "Describe SQLAlchemy constraint more clearly.

'<= 0.7.99' is an unclear way of saying '< 0.8', as well as being
technically buggy, as 0.7.100 could, in principle, be released.

Change-Id: Ib76f237dbe8e1879cf0899c7a8ce016e9b4b98e8
"}]
commit_message:
Describe SQLAlchemy constraint more clearly.

'<= 0.7.99' is an unclear way of saying '< 0.8', as well as being
technically buggy, as 0.7.100 could, in principle, be released.

Change-Id: Ib76f237dbe8e1879cf0899c7a8ce016e9b4b98e8

commit_message:
Correct lock path for storage-registry-lock

This fixes the lock path for storage-registry-lock to prevent a
potential data loss due to a race-condition scenario.  Since the
storage-registry-lock is used to modify a json blob that is
authoritative as to which nodes are using the storage so that
we don't remove any "in-use" backing files on the shared storage
segment (if in use).

The potential data-loss could occur in limited cases of the race
that the lock should prevent.  This can only occur if the image
cache cleanup is triggerd when a node has been eliminated from
the register_storage_use JSON incorrectly by this race condition.

Most of the time the race simplyresults in a corrupted json blob.

Fixes-bug: 1194696
Change-Id: Ib1a5785646e75dc90bdd2a7e69a697adc4fbb298

commit_message:
Update docs config

This commit updates the docs conf.py to make it more closely resemble
what is used it other projects(based on nova's equivilent file). It
also removes listing Sean Dague as the sole author for the Tempest
docs because it is a collaborative effort. It also fixes a pep8
failure on the imports.

Change-Id: I535858dc9d413e8d5f92d44194137f615390d117

commit_message:
Make some PEP8 understandable in run_tests.sh -p

Previously the error message is hard to understand when
some hacking violation such as H803 is detected.
It can be avoided by removing $included_dir from flake8 argument.
As excluded dir is defined in tox.ini, $inlucded_dir is not needed.

Change-Id: I8d1d48fa6feba74ffcec27bf971394b9db727945
Closes-Bug: #1229342

commit_message:
Store tenant with trust details in user_creds

Currently we don't store tenant name/ID to user_creds when a trust_id
is found in the context.  However as mentioned in bug #1231483 keystone
currently requires the tenant_id when re-scoping a token to a trust via
the v2 tokens API.

Change-Id: I5bd9cb914a8c9365ed30ece8e0a61ba1e0a3c4bc
Partial-Bug: #1227901

commit_message:
improve bulk document

This a very small change which just tell users request url of bulk
delete request. In original docstrings, it just states the request
parameters, request body and request method but not request url.

Change-Id: I0bbc302a0e072910bb58e4814614d7f761433b10

Register debug options when TempestConfig is initialized

This patch prevents failures from code which accesses debug options
from TempestConfig instances

Bug 1231743

Now we are using meaningful host names for seed and undercloud
machines, which is important for nova-compute to work properly.

setup-baremetal calls in devtest.sh seem to have swapped service
host names (when baremetal nodes are registered for undercloud

"}]
commit_message:
Swap service host names in setup-baremetal calls

Now we are using meaningful host names for seed and undercloud
machines, which is important for nova-compute to work properly.

setup-baremetal calls in devtest.sh seem to have swapped service
host names (when baremetal nodes are registered for undercloud
machine the 'seed' service host name is used and vice versa).

Change-Id: I1373eec38f28d6294f8d941f9b99f0781082a325

commit_message:
Make PM_* optional

These are optional arguments so need to be given a default as nounset is
set. This deals with "unbound variable" errors.

Change-Id: I1ee059aba29f4e7a546f110348b39cc9eb34ef4c

The debug configuration group is not registered

commit_message:
Get host group id when Huawei driver initializing

Get host group id when Huawei driver initializing to make sure
host group id won't be None after cinder node host sys reboot.

fixes bug 1230372

Change-Id: Ia3d5de116804930b2bb0035e4c991ebb9801ee76

commit_message:
Allow the user to toggle configuration of Apache

Up until now, Apache was configured along with Horizon, using the
Apache module's default params. While that works just fine in very
simple deployments, more advanced deployments will require control
over those params, e.g. to enable SSL.

Related-Bug: #1190282

Change-Id: Id8870f52601ac2a936a338686fbf29421cbcefa0

commit_message:
Create a Token / Endpoint Auth Plugin

Make the v2 and v3 client tests use this plugin. This provides the most
basic example of using an auth plugin and assures that the client tests
all still work without using the legacy wrapping plugins.

Change-Id: Ic868bf2ace35c53255e2c5fd9ac18f7ebc932dd3
Part of: blueprint auth-plugins

commit_message:
Move Auth Plugin concepts onto session

Create base client object as the most simple way of dealing with a
session on a client. Create auth plugins as a part of a session. Make
existing code use the common base code and classes.

Change-Id: I1739e16106c550624cf2ce4413ff1d80692ac3d0
Part of: blueprint auth-plugins

"}, {'account_id': 1782, 'date': '2013-09-15 13:09:21.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 1782, 'date': '2013-09-15 13:14:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

I had an impression that the expected_task_state, if not specified, is None and that is what passed to the db.update() method, similar to what happened before the Instance objects been introduced. The idea is that in case the vm current task state is different from expected=None it will fail on UnexpectedTaskStateError. It's not suppose to change existing task_state if it's not None.

But, after some testing found a bug 1225659 and proposed solution: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/46649

Regarding the question how it solves the problem: the vm evacuate api expects that vm task_state is None. In case it's not it will fail. Setting vm task_state to initing prevents evacuations to happen during the service init time window."}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2013-09-15 13:24:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-15 13:37:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Works for me

(1 inline comment)

Sorry but it looks like you're only considering the case of evacuated instances and not thinking about the impact of your change on any non-evacuated instances.

Comments in line, but just overwritting task_state is not the right thing to do here - there is other start-up processing that depends on task_state values.

A non-null task_state is meant to imply that an operation is in progress - and this new value breaks that paradigm.  For example on a compute-manager restart (where the host and Instance are still running) this change would set the task state in a way that could confuse users."}, {'account_id': 1782, 'date': '2013-09-20 08:22:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: (1 inline comment)

Phil. I described in the inline comment why the task_state will be never overwritten if it's not null, but basically it's due to expected_task_state=None in the instance save() method. It also related to the bug fix i proposed here because the current implementation has bug: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/46649
Sorry, maybe i missing something, but please point me to the place where it's got broken during host init flow in case the instance task_state changed from None to INITING in this short time window."}, {'account_id': 1501, 'date': '2013-09-20 12:25:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: (1 inline comment)

OK Thanks - I can see now that we don't lose any existing task_state.   I think this change does need to be set to depend on your other fix though - if it went if first it would break things.

I'm also still a bit concerned about the user seeing their instance going from Active(None) -> Active(Initing) -> Active(None) though.  I can see that possibly upsetting some users monitoring.  I'd like to see some other review opinions on that.

Finally I'm not really sure that this eliminates your race condition - as I understand it you want to block a new evacuate command while the compute-manager is starting, but  isn't there still a (agreed much smaller) window for that request to be made via the API between the call to get the list of instances and you setting the task_State on each one ?

This is a classic clustering / HA type issue, and normally addressed by stopping the original host from comming back up. It feels to me that what you're trying to fix here in the code would be better handled by a robust and documented system admin process.   Only an admin should be evacuating an instance - and they should be taking steps to make sure the original node doesn't restart while they are running evacuations.   If you really want to have some support for that in the codebase then there should be an attribute of the service table an admin can set to stop a service from restarting.

This just feels like the wrong place to be trying to fix this issue, and it won't be 100% effective."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-09-28 06:03:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Abandoned

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-09-28 06:03:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
Race condition during init_host

Solves race condition that potentially can lead to multiple instances
running from same disk on different hosts.
When compute service starts it checks whether managed instances
been evacuated to another host (in
manager._destroy_evacuated_instances). The time between this check and
when service appears to be active via servicegroup is a time when
instance can be evacuated to another host which will lead to duplicated
instances in the environment.

This patch solves it by keeping all the instances task_state in
"initing" until service initialization finished. In this way
evacuation of those instances can't be started.

Fix bug 1223431

Change-Id: I1065e9336fd0a9525ca983829ff60d702d4739a6

'}, {'account_id': 1, 'date': '2013-09-20 15:46:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I have a few concerns:

* Docker support requires a 3rd-party apt archive; I want to make sure we're okay with that (to date we have tried to stick to distro-supplied packages).

* The install script has external network dependencies.  We try to avoid those in the devstack-gate scripts because at the rate that we run tests, network issues show up all the time (and also sometimes it looks like we are running a DDoS on sites if the gate is busy).

Here http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack-dev/devstack/tree/tools/docker/install_docker.sh#n37 is where it adds the apt repo and installs packages from it.  If we wanted to use this repo, I think we'd want to have it added during the image creation step and ensure that the .deb files are cached (also during the image creation step).  Devstack would need to be updated to support testing wether the repo and key have already been added.  And ideally, devstack would add something to the 'apts' directory so that the needed packages would be automatically cached (that's where the image pre-cache script looks).

Also here http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack-dev/devstack/tree/tools/docker/install_docker.sh#n60 an image is downloaded.  That is defined in the hypervisor-docker file, but not in stackrc.  Compare that to openvz whose custom image _is_ defined in stackrc: http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack-dev/devstack/tree/stackrc#n246

If the docker image were set up similarly, it would be automatically picked up by the pre-cache scripts.  If that's not possible, we may need to special case it in the devstack image creation.

To summarize:

1) Let's get some consensus on the appropriateness of the docker apt repo.

2) Let's see if the docker construction in devstack can more closely follow the openvz model.

3) Anything in devstack we still can't normalize will need to be added to the image creation scripts (which are here, btw: http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack-infra/config/tree/modules/openstack_project/files/nodepool/scripts )"}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2013-09-20 15:50:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

One more complexity to consider with this is that docker requires kernel 3.8 or above: http://docs.docker.io/en/latest/installation/kernel/

That's not included in the precise image used today.  There is a newer kernel in the official ubuntu repo (linux-generic-lts-raring) that would work, in theory.  It would require using a different image for docker testing, or updating the image that everything uses."}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2013-09-20 15:50:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Work In Progress'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-09-28 06:03:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

commit_message:
Add docker support

The Havana release of Nova includes a new compute driver for docker.
This driver should be easy for us to test in the existing CI setup.
Support was added to devstack.  This adds a devstack-gate hook for
turning on docker.  The instructions say that you just have to put
VIRT_DRIVER=docker in your localrc and run the docker install script
before running stack.sh.

Change-Id: I1e972127b0e8d6053f6581a586c7b27279f296c9

commit_message:
Eliminate 1-line static _should_call_create_net() in Cisco plugin

Fixes bug 1205172

This fix eliminates a 1-line static method in virt_phy_sw_v2.py.
This 1-line static method was originally created so that this funcionality
could be mocked, but mocking is unnecesary if the compute host ID
is provided when neutron ports are created in unit testing.

Change-Id: I478bb75b0ef576cbfa2052b3a514de5aa43b0207

Franois, I ran into a blog post from June 10th[1] that proposes having Apache provide the keystone service on the same ports, so that nothing else has to be changed. I know that this post was written after you started this change, but is it something you'd consider implementing, or accepting if it were provided? It seems like it would be less disruptive to other services, and also make troubleshooting instructions from the docs easier to apply for novice users.

I've set this up in my environment and it seems to work fine (modulo that I listen to non-SSL only on localhost and use Apache to proxy SSL requests into it, so I haven't tested any of the native SSL stuff).

If SSL is enabled by default then why are the end points in the tests still using http? See 'with overriden public and private paths'.

I can't say I'm a fan of the way SSL is being enabled here, though it may be beyond the scope of this patch. ssl_setup is wholly inadequate to create SSL certs, even for a development environment IMHO. There should be new params created so the user can provide their own CA, cert and public key with at most calling ssl_setup if the user doesn't provide their own.

I tried testing this in a Havana environment, but I was unable to get far due to:

Error: Could not retrieve catalog from remote server: Error 400 on SERVER: Invalid parameter wsgi_daemon_process at /etc/puppet/environments/production/modules/keystone/manifests/wsgi/apache.pp:157 on node controller4.example.com

The Apache config is also lacking Listen for the configured ports.

I commented out the unknown variables, knowing the resulting config probably wouldn't work. I noticed that the eventlet keystone process was still running. Is it enough to apply the Apache version or does one need to exclude something as well?"}, {'account_id': 1918, 'date': '2013-09-19 14:30:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 17:

@Rob Crittenden

> If SSL is enabled by default then why are the end points in the tests still using http? See 'with overriden public and private paths'.

SSL is enabled by default _only_ for the apache/wsgi workers, not for keystone eventlet server.
These tests are not related to this changeset.

> I can't say I'm a fan of the way SSL is being enabled here, though it may be beyond the scope of this patch. ssl_setup is wholly inadequate to create SSL certs, even for a development environment IMHO. There should be new params created so the user can provide their own CA, cert and public key with at most calling ssl_setup if the user doesn't provide their own.

I'll add the 'ssl_*' [1] parameters (from apache::vhost) to the parameters. The current default lets the user handle the global SSL configuration with apache default values.

[1] https://github.com/puppetlabs/puppetlabs-apache/blob/master/manifests/vhost.pp#L71-L77

> I tried testing this in a Havana environment, but I was unable to get far due to:
Error: Could not retrieve catalog from remote server: Error 400 on SERVER: Invalid parameter wsgi_daemon_process at /etc/puppet/environments/production/modules/keystone/manifests/wsgi/apache.pp:157 on node controller4.example.com

What puppetlabs-apache module version are you using ? 
You should use at least version 0.9.0 which introduced new wsgi parameters.

> The Apache config is also lacking Listen for the configured ports.

puppetlabs-apache automatically adds the required Listen directives. [2] [3]

[2] https://github.com/puppetlabs/puppetlabs-apache/blob/master/manifests/vhost.pp#L66

[3] https://github.com/puppetlabs/puppetlabs-apache/blob/master/manifests/vhost.pp#L248-L255

> I commented out the unknown variables, knowing the resulting config probably wouldn't work. I noticed that the eventlet keystone process was still running. Is it enough to apply the Apache version or does one need to exclude something as well?

If using apache/wsgi keystone on port 443 there's no problem  running the eventlet keystone process running. If you don't want the eventlet keystone process running or if you want to run apache/wsgi keystone on ports 5000 & 35357, you have to disable the keystone service as seen in the examples/apache_dropin.pp line 33."}, {'account_id': 1918, 'date': '2013-09-19 17:51:13.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 18.'}, {'account_id': 1918, 'date': '2013-09-19 17:51:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 18:

commit_message:
Enable serving keystone from apache mod_wsgi

Serving keystone from a wsgi container is recommended for production
setups. SSL is enabled by default.

See the following URLs for explanations:
    http://adam.younglogic.com/2012/03/keystone-should-move-to-apache-httpd/
    https://etherpad.openstack.org/havana-keystone-performance

Documentation in manifests/wsgi/apache.pp

Apache can be configured as a drop in replacement for keystone (using
    ports 5000 & 35357) or with paths using the standard SSL port. See
examples in examples/apache_*.pp

- Also change some 'real_' prefix into '_real' suffix to respect the
coding guide.
- Added the '--insecure' option to keystone client in the provider to
allow using self-signed certificates.
- Fixed parsing the ssl/enable value in the provider.

Change-Id: Id0c95bc30ea5e33fe8add583afcccb28b7a6ce1f

commit_message:
Add host routes and dns nameservers to Midonet DHCP

In the Midonet plugin, the host routes and dns nameserver information
was not being passed down to the midonet client API. This fix addresses
this by passing down the correct information.

Change-Id: I142ad4ceccdcf8b0e13db55fa54513f82995efc5
Closes-Bug: #1229655

I don't think I introduced this:
http://logs.openstack.org/03/47603/3/check/gate-django_openstack_auth-pep8/e2841d3/console.html

Question:
Are horizon unittests launched with this django_openstack_auth patched version installed in horizon's unittest venv?
If not, it would be safer in order to ensure non-regressions.
So despite the provided unittests for django_openstack_auth, I also launched horizon's unittest after installing this patched version in a horizon venv, just to make sure."}, {'account_id': 1941, 'date': '2013-09-24 08:03:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I don't prefer the solution of revoking the scoped_token for every project switch, this will add load to Keystone, since it needs to regenerate the token every switch rather than re-using an existing token.

Maybe changing request.session['token_list'] into a set() can also fix the reported issue that the token_list keeps on growing for the back and forth project switch?"}, {'account_id': 8674, 'date': '2013-09-24 08:37:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Hy Lin Hua Cheng.

Changing the list to a set wouldn't solve the issue, because the token ID is diferent per each request (as per my tests), so the set (instead of the list) would still grow the same way.

I could "keep" the token without a request, but if you have PKI tokens, you would have a cookie blow up over 4 or 5 tenants...

I also retreiev a new token ID because as David Lyle said:
Sep 19 18:09:34 <david-lyle>	we have to request a new token even if it's in the dict because the service catalog or roles grants may have changed
Sep 19 18:09:52 <david-lyle>	if we use the old token, we won't pick up those changes

If I keep the old token, we would not be aware of catalog or role changes untill logout-login.

Also, Before my patch, keystone was overloaded by a batch request of a token list to delete... Which is not the case anymore.

Question:
Do I keep a dict of tokens per tenant id (the token id changes for each request so it can not be a dict key) and not request new tokens if I already have one for a tenant (but will not be aware of role changes) and we will have to also merge this?:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/46711/
Or do we still use this patch wich still reduces the keystone requests (a huge big reduction of requests per logout)?'}, {'account_id': 5623, 'date': '2013-09-25 21:02:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

I think the idea for the patch is sound.  

We maintain a list of tokens that we never reuse, nor can we due to potential catalog and role changes.  Deleting the tokens as we go versus all at once on logout should put less of a load on keystone in my estimation.

Also, consider the PKI case where 1 or 2 tokens could blow past the cookie size limit.

I would like to see a sanity check so that is a keystone backend is reusing the token ids, we don't revoke the new token.  Other than that change, I think the code is sound."}, {'account_id': 1941, 'date': '2013-09-25 22:48:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: No score

Hi Yves,

I was under the impression that Keystone re-uses token. My bad, you're correct that keeping Token ID does not make sense.

For PKI tokens, we only keep the hashed PKI token to make it smaller but at some point it we would still hit the cookie limit.

I digged into it further and I am okay with your patch to revoke the scoped token whenever project switches."}, {'account_id': 8674, 'date': '2013-09-26 13:46:30.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-26 13:48:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Works for me

commit_message:
Revoking token when switching tenant or loging out

Tokens where added to a list which was continuesly growing after each project
switch.
When session storage is configured to use signed cookies, this was leading to
having cookies growing above the 4KB limit.

Change-Id: I636ee34546a3a2bc59ae727cf8b1b64cd816e867
Closes-Bug: #1227754

commit_message:
Bump oslo.config version

This commit just bumps the minimum version requirement for
oslo.config. Version 1.2.0 has been released so we should keep
tempest's required version in sync with the other projects.

Change-Id: Ie78070a9fe0759c30fb84ac892a257e0c5cbf246

commit_message:
Adding checking to prevent conflict image size

Adding necessary checking to api v1 controller, to prevent client
provide conflict image size by '--location' and '--size' arguments.

Fixes bug: 1220744
docImpact

Change-Id: I0b846dd885ea6b675495058ac038eb9b5777fb81
Signed-off-by: Zhi Yan Liu <zhiyanl@cn.ibm.com>

commit_message:
Fix error when create user with LDAP backend

Creating users would fail when using the LDAP backend. The error
from the server was '400 Bad Request' with the message
'must be string, not None'.

The fix is to filter out 'None' attr names when creating a user.

Closes-Bug: #1231772

Change-Id: I747f39039b9c840a3e5861b66996dee328510cd6

commit_message:
Remove gettext_lazy of log message in nexus/profile impl

Marking log messages as translatable brings useless pain to tranlators
and all other log messages in Horizon are not marked as translatable.

Feedback from translators community

Change-Id: I13b20eacc5fda28011578e38290c9aea9a7ab600
Closes-Bug: #1230097

commit_message:
Enable execution of heat-manage db_sync

This patch is aiming to correct a fault in puppet-heat that was not
executing the heat-manage db_sync that was making this module in the
end not fully working.

At this stage there are no tests to support this change but I am
willing to add those in a later commit.

This patch it's been rebased according to this change: https://review.openstack.org/46227

This new patchset include a patch from Sebastien Badia and should
make all the tests green with Change id: I2aa8fc070e5f5ee18040200e4a5b4f6161550280

Change-Id: Ib7731ab429ea92947f52bcf015facc8864466586

commit_message:
Make neutron context able to handle db lock mode

This patch introduces the ability to set the lock mode
on a context. This allows to make queries aimed at
updating the state of the DB, thus solving potential
race conditions when multiple readers/writers are accessing
the DB whilst keeping the transactional isolation
level down.

Query objects with the specified lock mode can be obtained
using the context's utility method session_query().

Fixes bug #1228735

Change-Id: I717e8e9577913f45ca75aa235b15d20015edd595

commit_message:
Add vendor_passthru method to RPC API

Method vendor_passthru allows Ironic API
service validate and to pass vendor-specific
info to a node driver.

Partially implements blueprint pxe-mount-and-dd

Change-Id: I2c60d84e9d983a301c9169f3a1e9a34e93d2b050

commit_message:
Add a directory/filesystem based persistence layer

Add a nice non-memory-based but also non-db based
persistence layer which is another good example of
how a persistence layer can be created (and used).

Example directory structure:

  /books
  /books/247c5311-d4ec-461b-9e76-51830d6a75b2
  /books/247c5311-d4ec-461b-9e76-51830d6a75b2/metadata
  /books/247c5311-d4ec-461b-9e76-51830d6a75b2/flows
  /books/247c5311-d4ec-461b-9e76-51830d6a75b2/flows/25f18828-a067-411e-9035-8217536f925d
  /flows
  /flows/25f18828-a067-411e-9035-8217536f925d
  /flows/25f18828-a067-411e-9035-8217536f925d/metadata
  /flows/25f18828-a067-411e-9035-8217536f925d/tasks
  /flows/25f18828-a067-411e-9035-8217536f925d/tasks/a352fa2e-82cf-4c37-89ae-3aa10dbf1437
  /tasks
  /tasks/a352fa2e-82cf-4c37-89ae-3aa10dbf1437

Change-Id: I63aaf56497187e21469bc500a49dd02de0c67f29

This was relatively simple to fix, assuming that the image used
to boot the windows instance has the os_type set to "windows".
The use of os_type in this manner is consistent with the
existing use in the Xen hypervisor driver.

DocImpact: if you're booting windows instances, then you need to
set the os_type image property in glance to "windows". Otherwise
your instances will have their clock timezone set to UTC, which
has unexpected side effects in windows.

Change-Id: Id6759a290ed25c9add97ac61bb7d165b3fb908b2
Closes-Bug: 1231254
'}]
commit_message:
Windows instances require the timezone to be "localtime"

This was relatively simple to fix, assuming that the image used
to boot the windows instance has the os_type set to "windows".
The use of os_type in this manner is consistent with the
existing use in the Xen hypervisor driver.

DocImpact: if you're booting windows instances, then you need to
set the os_type image property in glance to "windows". Otherwise
your instances will have their clock timezone set to UTC, which
has unexpected side effects in windows.

Change-Id: Id6759a290ed25c9add97ac61bb7d165b3fb908b2
Closes-Bug: 1231254

commit_message:
Make sure periodic task sync_power_states continues on error

If an instance sync_power action fails with an exception, no more
instances will be synced. If the failure is permanent, this will block
other instances from having their power states synced for as long as
this keeps happening.

Make sure to catch and log such exceptions and then continue with the
next instance.

Change-Id: Ie3cf5d7f590cb680e712d76b7a32c630e82f362d
Closes-Bug: #1228160

commit_message:
Add a UUID attribute to security groups

The Neutron port resource requires a security group id.  Allow the
user to access this via GetAtt.

Change-Id: I587ce566312147ba06a5b4be57539ce97e793f14
Closes-Bug: #1224039

commit_message:
VMware: Fix SwitchNotFound error when network exists

In FlatNetworking mode, when a virtual network exists on the vCenter
host we still check for the presence of a physical adapter specified
in vlan_interface. This check is only needed if we are going to
create a new network on the vswitch associated with the interface.

This fix removes the check for the physical adapter and the vswitch
when network already exists.

Fixes: bug #1226238
Change-Id: I1eecf2c339534d8694ec6a8bdfaff5217ba2f8ef

commit_message:
Fix unicode string values missing in previous patch

Commit 61bedc9aa04b0bac21e5c4bd17d6d2c09e2d9e01 lost some code
around the str_or_none() helper in objects/utils.py during a
rebase which caused almost all of our values to not actually
be coerced to unicode. This adds that.

Also, the instance.uuid value can't (and shouldn't) be unicode,
so add a cstring() helper and convert it to use that so that
the above change doesn't try to make uuid be unicode. Also,
make str_value() enforce non-None-ness like cstring() to avoid
bugs where we get 'None' unexpectedly, and add a test for that
whole function, which was missing before.

Change-Id: I941545d38aee10f140610b268fbd9c744f6545f9

commit_message:
xenapi: enforce filters after live-migration

Currently and network filters, including security groups, are
lost after a server has been live-migrated.

This partially fixes the issue by ensuring that security groups are
re-applied to the VM once it reached the destination, and been started.

This leaves a small amount of time during the live-migrate where the VM
is not protected. There is a further bug raised to close the rest of
this whole, but this helps keep the VM protected for the majority of the
time.

Fixes bug 1202266

Change-Id: I84fdb6e2a8ee38d75f243aadbe79945af1d6849d

commit_message:
Remove deepcopy

Deep-copying is currently breaking traceback
storage, since tracebacks can't be deep-copied due
to an impl. detail of python that doesn't let a
user of python do this (in any sane way).

Change-Id: I923bee23d72623281698550ccfd9237c94422e93

[{'created': '2013-09-25 18:55:11.000000000', 'message': "Increase MTU on brbm (fixes iscsi packet loss)

iSCSI fails miserably when using an OVS bridge with the MTU
set to 1500. With it set to 1500 I repeatedly get iSCSI
connection errors in my iscsid log files.

This patch updates our setup-network script so that when we create brbm
we automatically set the MTU to 1504.

It also makes a note in devtest.md so that people using real bare metal
will know to increase their MTU's for the control plane to avoid
errors like this.

Change-Id: Iefdb0ab31769bc0a9cd15eab3948f3d78c35efdd

commit_message:
Add doc note about over-mtu packet loss.

In some cases (on Fedora 19, using *real*
bare metal, etc) users have seen over-mtu packet
loss when running iSCSI commands. In these
cases:

  iscsid: log shows repeated connection failed errors (and reconnect)

  dmesg shows:
    openvswitch: vnet1: dropped over-mtu packet: 1502 > 1500

This patch makes a note in devtest so that people who encounter
similar errors may know they need to increase their MTU
for the control plane.

Change-Id: Iefdb0ab31769bc0a9cd15eab3948f3d78c35efdd

commit_message:
Add power management support to register nodes.

This changes makes it possible to pass real pm_address, pm_user, and
pm_password parameters to the nova baremetal-node-create commands.

To use simply pass PM_IPS, PM_USERS, and PM_PASSWORDS parameters
(space delimited) so that the associated user:password combination
correspond to the MACS (which we already require to use this script)

The motivation for this change is to make it possible to use this
script (and follow the dev/test story) using *real* hardware and
not just fake VMs.

Change-Id: I347edeb3b81473305d64f74ea2ac78d731361c9d

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-09-27 13:27:39.000000000', 'message': "Clarify UTF-8 and URL-encoding of names

Fixes two issues:

o Where UTF-8 and URL-encoding are mentioned, often the URL-encoding is
  mentioned first. This might imply that URL-encoding is key -- it's not.
  The clasic mistake is to simply URL-encode a string. This can result in
  illegal UTF-8. Example:  (y-umlaut) is URL-encoded as %FF. Whereas,
  the correct UTF-8, then URL-encoding is %C3%BF.

o Where container and object names appear in headers (such as
  X-Versions-Location), the UTF-8 string must be URL-encoded. This fix
  clarifies the header descriptions of such headers.

Change-Id: I82dea0e789aab6eb9bf27a1e70b01de427d50b80
"}, {'created': '2013-09-27 16:11:21.000000000', 'message': "Clarify UTF-8 and URL-encoding of names

commit_message:
Clarify UTF-8 and URL-encoding of names

Fixes two issues:

o Where UTF-8 and URL-encoding are mentioned, often the URL-encoding is
  mentioned first. This might imply that URL-encoding is key -- it's not.
  The clasic mistake is to simply URL-encode a string. This can result in
  illegal UTF-8. Example:  (y-umlaut) is URL-encoded as %FF. Whereas,
  the correct UTF-8, then URL-encoding is %C3%BF.

o Where container and object names appear in headers (such as
  X-Versions-Location), the UTF-8 string must be URL-encoded. This fix
  clarifies the header descriptions of such headers.

Change-Id: I82dea0e789aab6eb9bf27a1e70b01de427d50b80

@llu - certainly if the drop_constraint() type_ parameter was the *only* reason for jumping forward to 6.0, i.e. to address https://bugs.launchpad.net/ceilometer/+bug/1221467 with https://review.openstack.org/46004 , then it seems like that was premature and could be reverted.

@svetlana: sure, it was merged in https://review.openstack.org/45391 , but the point is that this version jump seemed totally motivated by the usage of drop_constraint(type_) in those two ceilometer migrations, whereas the need for the newer version could be avoided by simply using using the old kwarg name.'}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2013-09-25 10:58:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@jd__: I'm not sure about the ordering of local versus global requirements when the lower bound is being reverted.

Sure, a forward jump necessitates that the global requirement is incremented before the local.

But would a backward jump involve the opposite ordering? (i.e. change local first, then global next, to avoid the lowered global requirement possibly breaking newly spun up devstacks)

Cheers,
Eoghan"}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2013-09-25 11:31:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

But our Jenkins is using alembic 6.0, so in order to keep our alembic version consistency on both build time and runtime, it is better that we keep 6.0 version, and another way is that can we change Jenkins alembic to 0.4.1?"}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2013-09-27 06:05:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

recheck no bug'}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2013-09-27 06:47:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Haomeng,Wang: well the way I interpret the lower bound in the requirements.txt is as an indication of the least version of a dependency that ceilometer is known to work against.

It is not a contract promised that we test against that particular version in the upstream CI env (as we generally take the highest available version from pypi or our mirror).

However it does provide guidance to distro packagers. If we leave that lower version at 6.0, it gives a strong indication that 6.0 *must* be packaged for their target OS. Whereas this version of alembic is not currently packaged for Fedora & derivatives.

But note that the distro packagers will continue to do their own CI against the particular versions of all dependencies that they intended to run against.

Cheers,
Eoghan'}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2013-09-27 08:28:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Avoid imposing alembic 6.0 requirement on all distros

Related-to: LP 1224666

Two of the alembic-based migrations use the new 'type_' kwarg in calls
to op.drop_constraint(), even though the old 'type' form was retained
for backward compatability:

  https://alembic.readthedocs.org/en/latest/ops.html

  "Changed in version 0.5.0: The type parameter is now named type_.
  The old name type will remain for backwards compatibility."

To avoid needlessly imposing the alembic 6.0 on distros for which this
version is not yet packaged, we revert these migrations to use the older
form.

The corresponding change to the global requirements is proposed here:

  https://review.openstack.org/48227

Change-Id: I3796ffa3de0e0f558f368d7ebf8e55c87657753d

commit_message:
Return parsed list value in CommaDelimitedList

What's `Ref' got from `CommaDelimitedList' parameter is unicode
string, so failed validation in properties.

The solution here is add list value in `CommaDelimitedList'.

Fixes bug #1226483

Change-Id: I5534ff6027d6f5be3a844778d025b73ab9500796

commit_message:
Skip None values in fixed_ips when creating Port

Neutron create port doesn't like when a None value is passed for
fixed_ips data, the value needing to be skipped instead. This patch
handles that problem for ip_address and subnet_id, as testing showed
that subnet_id wasn't mandatory.

Change-Id: I18a06cbad456eb75c41c299bc4c51c704d9dabc3

commit_message:
Don't publish samples if resource_id in missing

In swift API, the user can call uri without the resource_id.
This patch skip the samples publishing instead of raising the
exception:

Traceback (most recent call last):
File "ceilometer/objectstore/swift_middleware.py", line 109, in iter_response
    bytes_sent)
File "ceilometer/objectstore/swift_middleware.py", line 160, in publish_sample
    resource_id=account.partition('AUTH_')[2],
AttributeError: 'NoneType' object has no attribute 'partition'

It print the exception of the samples publishing failure instead of
raising a exception to never break the swift API.

Fixes bug #1223259

Change-Id: I5d90fa620c8f8ea82e86524b9703049257ca0345

commit_message:
Raise an exception if no router_id provided

IF both service neutron-l3-agent and neutron-server are up,
but no router id configured in /etc/neutron/l3_agent.ini, an
exception will be raised on DB as "DBError: IntegrityError",
because the variable router_ids has a default '' value that
doesn't match the DB grammar.

    * Check router id is specified in _init_() of l3 when
      not using namespace.
    * Move part of checking config params actions to new function
      _check_config_params()
    * Add corresponding unit tests.

Closes-Bug: #1226366

Change-Id: I905f8a4061c5b250782e025681dfefcc41c8c03c

commit_message:
Make availability zone for CinderVolume optional

So if end user does not specify, default availability zone will be
used.

Fixes bug #1231346

When registering baremetal hosts we used to hard code 'ubuntu'
everywhere.

With these two image element and heat template changes we can now set
the host names in nova.conf to 'seed' and 'undercloud' respectively:

 https://review.openstack.org/#/c/48497/
 https://review.openstack.org/#/c/48498/

This change updates register-nodes so that the $NODES variable is
used to create nova baremetal nodes. We already use this variable
to configure both the seed VM and undercloud so we may as well

Change-Id: I9eab3b310c3eb7455438d58de26f67bd9db04e58
"}, {'created': '2013-09-27 13:59:47.000000000', 'message': "Register meaningful service node names.

commit_message:
Register meaningful service node names.

When registering baremetal hosts we used to hard code 'ubuntu'
everywhere.

With these two image element and heat template changes we can now set
the host names in nova.conf to 'seed' and 'undercloud' respectively:

 https://review.openstack.org/#/c/48497/
 https://review.openstack.org/#/c/48498/

This change updates register-nodes (and setup-baremetal) so that
we pass in a $SERVICE_NODE parameter which is then used to register
baremetal nodes w/ Nova.

Change-Id: I9eab3b310c3eb7455438d58de26f67bd9db04e58

commit_message:
Redefine behavior for NvpAdvancedPlugin during network creation

When using the NvpAdvancedPlugin, *all* logical switches should
be created through VCNS. VCNS will then proxy the requests to
NVP. This patch implements such a behavior. This is achieved by
replacing the use of nvplib.create_lswitch with the one of the
vcns driver, as the remaining logic can be left as it is.

Fixes bug #1225011

Change-Id: I6c276f747d02ac0d4934c38bf2858cf9b73c5e24

commit_message:
add __str__ function to RestClient class

Most tempest tests are based on restfull http call.
Enable to easily explore the state of client object
 would be good for trouble shooting.

Thus, I would suggest to implement __str__ function for RestClient class.

 Closes-Bug: #1227474

Change-Id: If06dfc648a7458133e4f196bdca299f9531738b1

commit_message:
Update functionality implementation for manila api.

Currently manila api has no update functionality for
shares and snapshots. Update functionality added
to api and covered with unittests.

Change-Id: Ie11d3d822e7c8b3a83e66aca5989d3fc1605b0ba
Implements: blueprint share-update-feature

commit_message:
Send proper exception info as expected by the neutron client

The python neutron client for the V2 API expects the neutron API
to send information back such as the type and detail of the exception
in the body of the message

Change-Id: I9486d757258c4be72799c41102babe1f7923121c
Closes-bug: #1226400

commit_message:
actually register the debug_opts

In order to track down the neutron fails debugging routines were
added. However the optgroup for the debug flag was not registered
correctly, so we are getting a second fail when we ask if we
should try to debug the first fail.

Mark,

This is the last change in a set of around 5 to swift, cinder, nova and glance that I've been working on for around a year now. Its the final piece of a puzzle that allows a significant (potentially > 5x) performance boost for image snapshots/downloads when using ssl.

It would be *really* great to see this make havana. I will do any level of testing etc required.

Thanks!

-Stuart"}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2013-09-06 10:35:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

For reference here are the other patches:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/13466/ (glance client, Oct 13, 2012)
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/20029/ (swift client, Jun 11 2013)
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/32572/ (cinder, Jun 12 2013)
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/32562/ (nova, Jul 18 2013)

as I say, this one is the last one required for the following path:

nova -> glance client -> glance -> swift-client -> swift

Without this patch the "swift-client -> swift" will be a bottleneck running at 17 MB/s while the other parts can potentially reach 100 MB/s.

Note that since it is a parameter there is little risk here: indeed the new behaviour is off by default.'}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2013-09-06 10:45:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Sorry, looking more closely, the default for that setting should be "None", shouldn't it? That approach would maintain the behavior of having python swiftclient decide by basically leaving compression unspecified.

Do you buy that approach?'}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2013-09-11 11:52:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Hi Mark,

Here's the relevant swift client change:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/20029/

It parses the option as follows:


 def http_connection(url, proxy=None, ssl_compression=True):

 .
 .
 .

 if ssl_compression is True:
     conn = HTTPSConnection(host)
 else:
     conn = HTTPSConnectionNoSSLComp(host)

so to preserve the default behaviour I think we need to stick with 'True'.

You're right that the definition of the parameter is perhaps a bit woolly:
The client and server negotiate the compression algorithm. If we set the
parameter to False then we can say for sure that compression will be disabled.
However if we set it to True the client will attempt to negotiate
compression with the server but compression may or not happen depending
on what the server agrees to. 'None' may more accurately reflect the
latter, but I don't think we can use it without a change to the swift client.

I could change glance to omit the ssl_compression parameter altogether depending
on the value of the config file option, but that would require duplication
of the swiftclient.Connection function call."}, {'account_id': 616, 'date': '2013-09-20 21:44:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

After I check the comments between you and markwash, IMO I have to say shall we make a better name for the new option you added? to show the negotiation behavior for end user to prevent confused. And at least we should explain that in configuring.rst for the docs, also as flwang said. revisions:
[{'created': '2013-06-13 16:28:09.000000000', 'message': "Add swift_store_ssl_compression param

Add a new glance-api.conf parameter 'swift_store_ssl_compression',
which allows disabling SSL layer compression for https swift requests.

This can increase performance when transferring compressed images (eg
qcow2) to/from swift.

commit_message:
Add swift_store_ssl_compression param

Add a new glance-api.conf parameter 'swift_store_ssl_compression',
which allows disabling SSL layer compression for https swift requests.

This can increase performance when transferring compressed images (eg
qcow2) to/from swift.

Addresses bug 1190666.

DocImpact.

Change-Id: Ic26dba9dce5ea7e5c09fdd531746b93cec54fc5c

Hi Randall,

Can you outline the issues you face with the tests please?

I'm thinking we can do something similar to keystone, ie have a heat/contrib directory containing the resources, and create a heat/tests/contrib directory for the tests?

https://github.com/openstack/keystone/tree/master/keystone/contrib

I don't think the tests necessarily need to be optional, we just need to ensure any tests which require pyrax get skipped?"}, {'account_id': 7256, 'date': '2013-09-24 02:36:28.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 7256, 'date': '2013-09-24 02:41:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

That being said, the only sticky point with this patch IMO is using discover instead of testr for the contrib tests. I couldn't get that to work even with a test.conf in contrib. commit_message:
Move Rackspace resources into contrib

Using plain discover to run tests in contrib until
I can figure out how to make that work via testr.

Closes bug: 1220798

Change-Id: I5669b90152efabfacbc4b786a67cd1f4b139521a

but that becomes redundant when we switch to using neutron's DHCP

"}]
commit_message:
Switch to using a dedicated TFTPd for baremetal.

We currently use dnsmasq to provide TFTP when booting baremetal nodes,
but that becomes redundant when we switch to using neutron's DHCP
agent. Instead we need a dedicated TFTPd, and we can use that with
dnsmasq by disabling dnsmasq's built-in TFTPd, giving a consistent
setup.

Change-Id: I985fff9a3dded1b0dffe82fa5d48009441777733

setting the SUFFIX.

'}]
commit_message:
Correct baremetal service SUFFIX

The current SUFFIX setting is incorrectly appending /v1 when
registering the baremetal service, resulting in a 404 error
from the Ironic cli. This patch fixes the error by correctly
setting the SUFFIX.

Change-Id: I5103e58d3a69f750b40065bd7557ea8006897c94

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-09-17 22:56:24.000000000', 'message': "Create baremetal nodes and register them in lockstep

It's pretty confusing that we create 3 baremetal nodes towards the
beginning of the instructions, add 1 to the seed cloud and then
later add the other 2 to the undercloud.

We can easily create the required number of new nodes and immediately
register them when they're needed.

This makes it a lot more clear what you need to do if you want to
recreate just the baremetal node for running the undercloud.

Change-Id: I9e669c83fb9403acf939458afa8fcf2d27d18f5e
"}, {'created': '2013-09-18 16:56:31.000000000', 'message': "Create baremetal nodes and register them in lockstep

commit_message:
Create baremetal nodes and register them in lockstep

It's pretty confusing that we create 3 baremetal nodes towards the
beginning of the instructions, add 1 to the seed cloud and then
later add the other 2 to the undercloud.

We can easily create the required number of new nodes and immediately
register them when they're needed.

This makes it a lot more clear what you need to do if you want to
recreate just the baremetal node for running the undercloud.

Change-Id: I9e669c83fb9403acf939458afa8fcf2d27d18f5e

commit_message:
Handle HOT param constraints in provider templates

When HOT templates are used as provider templates, parameter constraints
have to be translated into provider resource properties correctly. The
properties Schema class has been design to cover both CFN and HOT, but
the code in Schema.from_parameter has to distinguish between CFN and
HOT parameter constraints to correctly build the schema.

This patch fixes the handling of HOT parameters.

Change-Id: I59027d3b51e5d6dcc2a867cc5b5015cd6c88051c
Closes-Bug: #1224111

commit_message:
For Subnet gateway_ip, pass None for empty string

A None gateway_ip has special meaning for create_subnet but
properties sanitise None values to be empty strings.

With this change, the following properties should all result
in gateway_ip=None being passed to create_subnet:
gateway_ip: null
gateway_ip: ~
gateway_ip: ''

Change-Id: I234542f7f2d7bddf7dee01f8a9c56c021b5f0c8c
Closes-Bug: #1226666

So, my default instinct is that we shouldn't make changes like this ...

However, this is currently only used for notifications related to host aggregate operations and was added during the Havana cycle by Jay himself in I2dc42addb587c4765b41e464697f35b1f844fde9

That makes the change less worrying - it's a limited set of notifications, added in Havana so unlikely to be widely used and it's the person who added the notifications originally who is requesting the change

commit_message:
Change service id to compute for compute/api.py

Now the default service id for nova api notification is aggregate,
this is not accurate, we should change it to compute.

Fix bug 1225579

Change-Id: Ife558024c57d9fd035cd1a618063c656e03c52a3

Add string presentation type in debug msg

By default, '%u' format is used which is not what we want.
Add '%s' format for 'name' in the debug msg.

Change-Id: Ie2c3929518cebd2135c4016f0abb9196662d545e
Closes-bug: #1231837

commit_message:
xenapi: ignore 500 errors from agent resetnetwork

Old versions of the FreeBSD and Gentoo agent return 500 on successful
resetnetwork calls. This changes the current error checking to treat 500
as a successful response for resetnetwork calls.

Fixes bug 1223818
Change-Id: Ia3eea109b6c3186af77124c704f13b70b0b91e81

commit_message:
Ensure we don't end up with invalid exceptions again

We've recently had a few (three?) exceptions where the messages
didn't work because there was a typo in the exception variable
name. This change adds a very simple unit test which ensures that
we don't end up in that state again.

Have you considered also turning on and testing other verbs, like DELETE and POST? They have to be enabled in the proxy config (backward compatibility is sometimes annoying; sorry about that), but they do work.

Also, I don't know if it's made it out to the docs yet, but X-Account-Meta-Temp-Url-Key-2 is also a spot to store a key, so you can have two. It's for seamless key rotation. commit_message:
Adds more test to cover Swift tempURL middleware

The patch moves away the single test existing from
test_object_services.py to its own file.

It then adds more tests to validate other HTTP
verbs like PUT and HEAD.

blueprint test-swift-tempurl-middleware

Change-Id: I1d7b021e8e3749b58a9fa657c709fb7154bd104e

commit_message:
Add flavor name validation when create flavor

Check flavor name when create flavor, raise bad request instead
of internal error when flavor name isn't present in request.

Change flavor unit tests to make flavor create request body
validation being tested.

Closes-Bug: 1220087

Co-authored-by: Takashi Natsume <natsume.takashi@lab.ntt.co.jp>
Change-Id: I3ec1642305590aff61e54252405420082ac2f596

commit_message:
Update rootwrap with code from oslo

These are all minor changes bringing nova up to commit c03f247

c03f247 Skip hidden files while traversion rootwrap filters
3f4d1d5 Fix os.getlogin() problem with no tty
fc04531 Send rootwrap exit error message to stderr
3663010 rootwrap: improve Python 3 compatibility
28395d9 Fixes files with wrong bitmode

Fixes bug #1231206

Change-Id: I9f5faefc769fb37d37b6f093fe3a11a6e9f650d4

commit_message:
Fix TempestConfig instance has no attribute 'debug'

Commit aeeeefd89ce16306b12b573f2e61b122e5578070 add debug capability
for basic network informations, but forget to register new added
options, this patch fixes it.

Change-Id: I04f7bdba145e78a3b3432b14467d790182eb0453
Closes-Bug: 1231775

commit_message:
Fix the wrong key name in nova REST API

The scheduler filter can be specified when create a server.
In the filter body of this example, the 'hypervisor' and
'near' is not valid key name, fix this.

Change-Id: Id03d9fae39cdbc053578575079a21ab72d15aed8

I see you also made a comment about moosefs, but I cannot for the life of me find it in the gerrit system :)

My guess was it was asking for justification for the removal, so here's my attempt:

Scope.

There is no special "OpenStack integration" for mounting a shared filesystem for ephemeral storage. It's just standard sysadmin stuff that should be covered well by their own upstream guides. So, if we document MooseFS for Ephemeral Storage we should also document: NFS, CephFS, GlusterFS, ExtremeFS, GPFS, CIFS and pNFS (have seen all used). Then for each of these there would be nothing special other than "mount it on /var/lib/nova/instances".'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-26 08:02:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Works for me
